 /> 76% and 76 out of 100 for the Xbox version;<ref name=\"GRXB\" /><ref name=\"MCXB\" /> 74.37% and 75 out of 100 for the PSP version;<ref name=\"GRPSP\" /><ref name=\"MCPSP\" /> and 72.75% and 71 out of 100 for the DS version.<ref name=\"GRDS\" /><ref name=\"MCDS\" />\n\n''[[Games for Windows: The Official Magazine|Games for Windows]]'' gave the PC version a score of five out of ten.<ref name=\"Games for Windows\">{{cite journal |last=Zuniga |first=Todd |date=October 2007 |title=Madden NFL 08: Behind the Times |magazine=[[Games for Windows: The Official Magazine]] |issue=11 |page=68 }}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the Mobile phone version a score of eight out of ten and called it \"a solid improvement over last year's edition, which was certainly no slouch on the field. The new passing controls are fantastic and will be appreciated by anybody new or returning to the series. The rest of the production is good, from the sound effects to the ability to monkey around with the stats and rosters. If you're a football fan, this is a definite download.\"<ref name=\"ignmobile\">{{cite web |last=Buchanan |first=Levi |date=August 22, 2007 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/08/22/madden-nfl-08-review |title=Madden NFL 08 Review (Cell) |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nMadden NFL 08 was included in [[EA Sports 08 Collection]] for [[Personal computer|PC]]'s on September 22, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |date= n.d.|url=https://www.gamespot.com/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Scott The Woz==\nThe [[YouTube]] comedy video game review series and channel Scott The Woz, created by Scott Wozniak, features Madden '08 as a running gag,<ref>{{cite interview |last=Wozniak |first=Scott |interviewer=Anthony Elio |title=YouTube's Scott Wozniak Discusses Creativity and Challenges on the Internet |url=https://innotechtoday.com/youtubes-scott-wozniak/ |date=June 19, 2018 |work=Innovation and Tech Today |access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> including having several copies of the game in the background of all of his videos. He also considers it the best game of the series and created a Christmas special based around it (including every version of the game) and the modern Madden franchise<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66treaoATsA| title = A Very Madden 08 Christmas - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = December 17, 2017| accessdate = April 15, 2020}}</ref> and had [[Vince Young]] (player on the game cover) be in his 2019 Christmas special titled 'It's a Bargain Bin Christmas'<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x31rjxZCw_k| title = It's a Bargain Bin Christmas - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = December 23, 2020| accessdate = April 15, 2020}}</ref> by purchasing him off of [[Cameo]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.reddit.com/r/scottthewoz/comments/efz96l/thank_you_ama/fc3o00u/| title = Reddit / ScottTheWoz: Yeah I was freakin' out a b ...|work = [[Reddit]]|first = Scott |last = Wozniak| date = December 26, 2019| accessdate = April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[NCAA Football 08]]\n* [[All-Pro Football 2K8]]\n* [[Blitz: The League II]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.easports.com/ Official EA Sports website]\n* [https://archive.is/20070514023652/http://maddenfb.com/blogs/Game/default.aspx EA developer's blog]\n* {{moby game|id=/madden-nfl-08}}\n\n{{MaddenNFL-Games}}\n\n[[Category:2007 video games]]\n[[Category:Madden NFL]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts games]]\n[[Category:Wii Wi-Fi games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Portable games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo DS games]]\n[[Category:GameCube games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:Wii games]]\n[[Category:Sports video games with career mode]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "IanTEB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madden_NFL_08"}
{"title_page": "NFL GameDay (video game series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game series\n| title = NFL GameDay\n| image = \n| caption = \n| platforms = [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]]\n| developer = [[989 Sports]]\n| publisher = 989 Sports\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| first release version = ''NFL GameDay''\n| first release date = November 21, 1995\n| latest release version = ''NFL GameDay 2005''\n| latest release date = August 1, 2004\n}}\n\n'''''NFL GameDay''''' is a series of [[American football]] video games for both the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[PlayStation 2]] video game consoles. ''NFL GameDay'' directly competed with [[EA Sports]]' ''[[Madden NFL]]'' Football and [[Sega]]'s [[NFL 2K]] franchises. The ''NFL GameDay'' series began with ''NFL GameDay'' released for the [[1995 NFL season|1995-96 NFL season]] and ended with ''NFL GameDay 2005'' following EA's acquisition of exclusive NFL licensing. The games were designed by [[989 Sports]] throughout their ten-year duration.\n\n==''NFL GameDay''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay (video game)}}\n''NFL GameDay'' is the first video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released in 1996 on the PlayStation by [[989 Sports|Sony Interactive Studios America]] as a competitor to the [[Madden NFL|Madden]] football game series. Its cover athlete is [[William Floyd (American football)|William Floyd]].\n\nThe game makes use of [[motion capture]] for its animations.<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=The Next Generation 1996 Lexicon A to Z: Motion Capture|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=15 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=March 1996|page=37}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay '97''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 97}}\n''NFL GameDay '97'' is the second video game in the NFL GameDay series. It was released on November 30, 1996 on the PlayStation by Sony Interactive Studios America. On the cover is [[Daryl Johnston]]. ''Gameday 97'' includes new options & features like season-ending injuries, a full-fledged draft, more statistics, and the ability to create players. It features all 30 NFL teams (1,500 [[National Football League Players Association|NFLPA]] players) and modeled stadiums, including real NFL uniforms with real logos and numbers.\n\nMotion capture was again used, with [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] being the motion capture actor.<ref name=EGM89>{{cite magazine|first=|last= |title=The Making of NFL GameDay '97 |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=89|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=December 1996|pages=306\u20137}}</ref> In order to avoid a common complaint against competitor ''Madden NFL'' - that the A.I. can consistently be beaten with a specific play - the developers hired a full-time game tester whose job was specifically to find such plays and report them so that a counter could be developed.<ref name=EGM89/>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 98''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 98}}\nNFL GameDay 98 is the third video game in the NFL GameDay series. It was released July 31, 1997 on the PlayStation by Sony Interactive Studios America. On the cover is [[Jerome Bettis]]. It was the first football video game to feature [[Polygonal modeling|3D polygonal graphics]]; it took longer for football games to adopt fully polygonal graphics than other genres because their large number of players and requisite fast pace made it difficult to do so at a reasonable [[frame rate]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=NFL GameDay '98: Sony's Incredible 3-D Football Game Gains the Graphical Edge |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=98|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=September 1997|page=124}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 99''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 99}}\n''NFL GameDay 99'' is the fourth game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released July 31, 1998 on the PlayStation, and August 31, 1998 on the PC, both by [[989 Sports]]. On the cover is [[Terrell Davis]].\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2000''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 2000}}\n''NFL GameDay 2000'' is the fifth video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released July 31, 1999 on the PlayStation by 989 Sports. On the cover is Terrell Davis.<ref name=\"NFL_2000_release\">{{cite web |title=NFL GameDay 2000 Redefines Football Videogame Category |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_August_9/ai_55388704/ |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=August 9, 1999 |accessdate=2011-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2001''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 2001}}\n\n''NFL GameDay 2001'' is the sixth video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series, and the first to be released on the [[PlayStation 2]]. It was released October 30, 2000 on the PlayStation, and November 20, 2000 on the PlayStation 2, both by 989 Sports. On the cover is [[Marshall Faulk]].<ref name=\"NFL_2001_release\">{{cite web |title=NFL GameDay(TM) 2001 for the PlayStation(R) Game Console Hits the Line At Full Speed on August 15. |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/NFL+GameDay%28TM%29+2001+for+the+PlayStation%28R%29+Game+Console+Hits+the...-a064145374 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=August 14, 2000 |accessdate=2011-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2002''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay 2002}}\n\n''NFL GameDay 2002'' is the seventh video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released August 6, 2001 on the PlayStation, and December 4, 2001<ref name=\"NFL_2002_PS2_release\">{{cite web |title=NFL GameDay(TM) 2002 Now Available for Gridiron Action On the PlayStation(R)2 Computer Entertainment System |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/All+New+and+Redesigned+NFL+GameDay%28TM%29+2002+Now+Available+for...-a080595728 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=December 4, 2001 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref> on the PlayStation 2, both by 989 Sports. On the cover is [[Donovan McNabb]].<ref name=\"NFL_2002_PS2_release\"/><ref name=\"NFL_2002_release\">{{cite web |title=NFL GameDay(TM) 2002 Takes to the Gridiron for Another PlayStation(R) Season. |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/NFL+GameDay%28TM%29+2002+Takes+to+the+Gridiron+for+Another+PlayStation%28R%29...-a077022314 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=August 7, 2001 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2003''==\n''NFL GameDay 2003'' is the eighth video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released August 13, 2002<ref>{{cite web |title=989 Sports(R) Kicks Off the Football Season with NFL GameDay(TM) 2003 for Both PlayStation(R) and PlayStation(R)2 Platforms |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/989+Sports%28R%29+Kicks+Off+the+Football+Season+with+NFL+GameDay%28TM%29+2003...-a090831828 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=August 13, 2002 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref> on the PlayStation and PlayStation 2, both by 989 Sports. On the cover is [[Tom Brady]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Tom Brady Signs on as Cover Athlete for 989 Sports(R)' NFL GameDay(TM) 2003 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Super+Bowl+XXXVI+MVP+Tom+Brady+Signs+on+as+Cover+Athlete+for+989...-a086011605 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=May 16, 2002 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2004''==\n''NFL GameDay 2004'' is the ninth video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released September 13, 2003 on the PlayStation and PlayStation 2, both by 989 Sports. On the cover is [[LaDainian Tomlinson]].<ref name=\"NFL_2004_release\">{{cite web |title=989 Sports(R) Kicks Off the Football Season with the Release of NFL GameDay(TM) 2004 for PlayStation(R)2 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/989+Sports%28R%29+Kicks+Off+the+Football+Season+with+the+Release+of+NFL...-a0106896838 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=August 26, 2003 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2005''==\n''NFL GameDay 2005'' is the tenth and final game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series, and unlike the last few GameDay video games, it is only available on the PlayStation console, and not on the PlayStation 2. It was released on August 1, 2004. On the cover is [[Derrick Brooks]]. It was the last first-party (Sony) game published for the PlayStation though there were sporadic official releases in 2005 and 2006 by others.\n\n==See also==\n*''ESPN Sunday Night NFL'', Sony's predecessor for [[SNES]], [[Sega Genesis]] and [[Sega CD]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nfl Gameday}}\n[[Category:National Football League video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Sony Interactive Entertainment franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game series\n| title = NFL GameDay\n| image = \n| caption = \n| platforms = [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]]\n| developer = [[989 Sports]]\n| publisher = 989 Sports\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| first release version = ''NFL GameDay''\n| first release date = November 21, 1995\n| latest release version = ''NFL GameDay 2005''\n| latest release date = August 1, 2004\n}}\n\n'''''NFL GameDay''''' is a series of [[American football]] video games for both the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[PlayStation 2]] video game consoles. ''NFL GameDay'' directly competed with [[EA Sports]]' ''[[Madden NFL]]'' Football and [[Sega]]'s [[NFL 2K]] franchises. The ''NFL GameDay'' series began with ''NFL GameDay'' released for the [[1995 NFL season|1995-96 NFL season]] and ended with ''NFL GameDay 2005'' following EA's acquisition of exclusive NFL licensing. The games were designed by [[989 Sports]] throughout their ten-year duration.\n\n==''NFL GameDay''==\n{{Main|NFL GameDay (video game)}}\n''NFL GameDay'' is the first video game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series. It was released in 1996 on the PlayStation by [[989 Sports|Sony Interactive Studios America]] as a competitor to the [[Madden NFL|Madden]] football game series. Its cover athlete is [[William Floyd (American football)|William Floyd]].\n\nThe game makes use of [[motion capture]] for its animations.<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |