 2003 |accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==''NFL GameDay 2005''==\n''NFL GameDay 2005'' is the tenth and final game in the ''NFL GameDay'' series, and unlike the last few GameDay video games, it is only available on the PlayStation console, and not on the PlayStation 2. It was released on August 1, 2004. On the cover is [[Derrick Brooks]]. It was the last first-party (Sony) game published for the PlayStation though there were sporadic official releases in 2005 and 2006 by others.\n\n==See also==\n*''ESPN Sunday Night NFL'', Sony's predecessor for [[SNES]], [[Sega Genesis]] and [[Sega CD]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nfl Gameday}}\n[[Category:National Football League video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Sony Interactive Entertainment franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Angeldeb82", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNFL GameDay 2002", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFL_GameDay_(video_game_series)"}
{"title_page": "Allan Fung", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Allan Fung\n|image       = Allan Fung.jpg\n|office      = Mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]]\n|term_start  = January 5, 2009\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Michael Napolitano]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Allan Wai-Ket Fung\n|native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hant|\u99ae\u5049\u5091}}}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1970|2|25}}\n|birth_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Barbara Ann Fenton\n|education   = [[Rhode Island College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[Suffolk University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n'''Allan Wai-Ket Fung''' (born February 25, 1970) is an American attorney and politician who has been mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island]], since 2009. He was the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Rhode Island]] in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]] and [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018 election]].\n\nElected mayor in 2008, Fung became the first mayor of Chinese ancestry in Rhode Island. Fung was previously a state prosecutor and attorney on legislative and regulatory affairs before serving on the Cranston City Council as a citywide councilman.\n\nHe lost the gubernatorial race in Rhode Island during 2014 and 2018 to Democrat [[Gina Raimondo]].\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAllan W. Fung ({{zh|t=\u99ae\u5049\u5091}}), born on February 25, 1970, at [[Providence Lying-In Hospital]] (now known as [[Women & Infants Hospital]]), Fung is the eldest of Kwong Wen and Tan Ping's three children. [[Crown colony]] Chinese immigrants from [[British Hong Kong]], his family settled in Rhode Island in 1969, and ran a small business on Cranston Street and Gansett Avenue, Cranston, RI.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cowart|first=Jen|title=Family Fundamental to Fung's career|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/Family-fundamental-to-Fungs-career,87554|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Cranston Herald|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nFung graduated from [[Classical High School]] in Providence, RI in 1988, in the same class as future Providence mayor [[Angel Taveras]]. He earned a B.A. from [[Rhode Island College]] in 1992. He received a Juris Doctor (J.D.) law degree from [[Suffolk University]] Law School in 1995. He received the Classical High School Distinguished Alumni Award in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Distinguished Alumni Awards|url=http://classicalalumni.org/alumni-awards-bios-2009.php|publisher=Classical High School Alumni Association|accessdate=22 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523012705/http://classicalalumni.org/alumni-awards-bios-2009.php|archive-date=2014-05-23|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nFung met Barbara Ann Fenton, a physical therapist, at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]].<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> They married in summer 2016.<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> Fung converted to Catholicism before the wedding.<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> Fung remains a devoted multicultural American with experience in both religious Americana, and United States diversity culture.\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Mayor Fung and Olivia Culpa, Miss USA 2012.jpg|thumb|Fung honors Cranston resident [[Olivia Culpo]] with a key to the City, after her coronation as [[Miss USA 2012]].]]\n[[File:Cranston mayor Allan Fung July 4 2016.jpg|thumb|Fung marched in the 2016 [[Bristol Fourth of July Parade]] with his wife Barbara Ann Fenton.]]\n\nPrior to his municipal leadership career, from 1999 to 2001, Fung served as a prosecutor, acting as Special Assistant, for the Rhode Island Attorney General.<ref>http://www.linkedin.com/in/afung1</ref> Fung served from 2001 to 2009 as the government relations counsel for Metropolitan Life Insurance Company [[MetLife]]. In 2003, he was elected to the Cranston, RI City Council. In 2004, Fung was honored as a Rhode Island Bar Foundation Fellow. He was also a [[Providence Business News]] 40 Under Forty honoree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbn.com/RI-voters-overwhelmingly-OK-bondsbr-re-elect-Kennedy-Langevin-and-Reed-,36144?print=1|title=R.I. voters overwhelmingly OK bonds, re-elect Kennedy, Langevin and Reed - Providence Business News|work=Providence Business News|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407101949/http://www.pbn.com/RI-voters-overwhelmingly-OK-bondsbr-re-elect-Kennedy-Langevin-and-Reed-,36144?print=1|archive-date=7 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Fung was chairman of the Rhode Island Governor's Insurance Council from 2005 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warwick.uber.matchbin.com/printer_friendly/2510188|title='Classical act' honors new mayor|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he was elected mayor in November 2008, beating [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Cynthia M. Fogarty by 63% to 37%. He is the first [[Chinese American]] elected as mayor in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelapa.com/2009/01/allan-fung-rhode-island-first-asian.html|title=Mayor Fung sworn in Monday night|date=5 January 2009|work=WPRI|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slanteyefortheroundeye.com/2009/01/go-go-mayer-allan-fong.html|title=Slant Eye For The Round Eye: Go Go Mayer Allan Fong|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> He succeeded [[Michael Napolitano]], who defeated him for the position in the 2006 election by 79 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/local_wpri_cranston_mayoral_race_20081029|title=Fung wins Cranston's mayoral race|work=WPRI|accessdate=17 November 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130209130248/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/local_wpri_cranston_mayoral_race_20081029|archive-date=2013-02-09|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.providencejournal.com/politics/2006/12/ri-gop-starts-s.html|title=RI GOP starts search for new leader|date=20 December 2006|work=Providence Journal|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> Fung was re-elected in 2010 against Richard R. Tomlins by 76% to 24% and in 2012 against only write-in opponents by 97% to 3%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cranstononline.com/stories/Dems-come-on-strong,76534?category_id=4&town_id=3&sub_type=stories|title=Dems come on strong|last=Fraser|first=Meg|date=7 November 2012|work=Cranston Herald|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> Fung is a council member for the [[Republican National Committee]]'s Asian Pacific American Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asianrepublicans.ning.com|title=THE ASIAN REPUBLICAN NETWORK - Network of Asian Republicans|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625004814/http://asianrepublicans.ning.com/|archive-date=2014-06-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gop.com/general/rnc-launches-national-advisory-councils/|title=RNC Launches National Advisory Councils - GOP|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Edgar|first=Randall|title=Fung Named to RNC Asian American Pacific Advisory Council|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140305-fung-named-to-rnc-asian-pacific-american-advisory-council.ece|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Providence Journal|date=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFung won re-election to a fourth term as Cranston mayor in November 2016, by a landslide ratio of 2 to 1.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Gregory|title=Cranston Mayor Allan W. Fung wins reelection in a landslide|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20161108/cranston-mayor-allan-w-fung-wins-reelection-in-landslide|accessdate=18 November 2016|publisher=The Providence Journal|date=8 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder Fung's leadership, Cranston became one of the Top 50 Cities to Live in America for three years in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/for-third-year-cranston-makes-list-of-50-best-cities,119249|title=For third year, Cranston makes list of '50 Best Cities'|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>  Cranston was also named one of the Top 100 Best Cities to Raise A Child in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alarms.org/best-cities-to-raise-kids-2017/|title=Best Cities to Raise Kids, 2017 - National Council For Home Safety and Security|website=www.alarms.org|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gubernatorial campaigns===\n\n====2014====\n[[File:Mayor Allan Fung visits Providence (cropped).jpg|thumb|Fung in 2014]]\n{{main|2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election}}\nIn November 2013, Fung announced his candidacy for [[Governor of Rhode Island]] in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://woonsocket.patch.com/groups/elections/p/mayor-fung-announces-bid-for-governor-woonsocket|title=Mayor Fung Announces Bid For Governor|date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=November 4, 2013|work=Woonsocket Patch|author=Rob Borkowski|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105155908/http://woonsocket.patch.com/groups/elections/p/mayor-fung-announces-bid-for-governor-woonsocket|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Allan Fung Announces Run for Governor of Rhode Island|url=http://www.8asians.com/2013/11/20/allan-fung-announces-run-for-governor-of-rhode-island/|work=8 Asians|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Howell|first=John|title=Fung stresses jobs in bid for Governor|url=http://www.cranstononline.com/stories/Fung-stresses-jobs-in-bid-for-governor,87133|accessdate=4 December 2013|newspaper=Cranston Herald|date=6 November 2013}}</ref> He received several high-profile Republican endorsements during the campaign, including former Rhode Island Governor [[Lincoln Almond]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edgar|first1=Randall|title=Former governor Lincoln Almond endorses Fung in governor\u2019s race|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140528-former-governor-lincoln-almond-endorses-fung-in-governors-race.ece|accessdate=13 September 2014|publisher=Providence Journal|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> former [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts Governor]] and 2012 presidential nominee [[Mitt Romney]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fowler|first1=Jack|title=Romney Supports Fung|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/387241/romney-supports-fung-jack-fowler|accessdate=13 September 2014|publisher=National Review|date=5 September 2014}}</ref> and former Massachusetts Governor [[William Weld]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Weld Endorses Fung for Governor|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/politics/weld-endorses-fung-for-governor|website=GoLocalProv.com|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> On September 9, 2014, Fung defeated [[Ken Block (politician)|Ken Block]] in the Republican primary, with a 55% majority.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kittridge|first1=Dan|title=Fung wins GOP primary|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/Fung-wins-GOP-primary,95933|accessdate=11 September 2014|agency=Cranston Herald|publisher=Beacon Communications|date=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Schieldrop|first1=Mark|title=Fung wins GOP Nomination for Governor|url=http://patch.com/rhode-island/cranston/fung-wins-gop-nomination-governor-0#.VBSnwi5dUbo|website=Cranston Patch|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Edgar|first1=Randall|last2=Bogdan|first2=Jennifer|title=Cranston's Mayor Fung clinches hard-fought GOP race over Block|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140909-cranstons-mayor-fung-clinches-hard-fought-gop-governors-primary-over-businessman-video.ece|accessdate=14 September 2014|publisher=Providence Journal|date=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914073329/http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140909-cranstons-mayor-fung-clinches-hard-fought-gop-governors-primary-over-businessman-video.ece|archive-date=2014-09-14|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Statewide Primary|url=http://www.ri.gov/election/results/2014/statewide_primary/|website=RI.gov|publisher=State of Rhode Island Board of Elections|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Soon thereafter, the [[Republican Governors Association]] President also endorsed him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/10/19/fung-republicans-see-opening-governor-race/4dBrGPRtMb2vbL4vrGhSOM/story.html|title=Fung, Republicans see opening in governor\u2019s race - The Boston Globe|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://johnstonsunrise.net/stories/In-Johnston-Christie-touts-Fungs-odds-in-race-for-governor,97017|title=In Johnston, Christie touts Fung\u2019s odds in race for governor|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref> Democrat [[Gina Raimondo]] would go on to win the three-way contest by a 4-point margin.<ref>{{cite web|last=HERBST-BAYLISS|first=SVEA|agency=Reuters|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|accessdate=November 4, 2014|url=\nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/05/us-usa-elections-rhodeisland-governor-idUSKBN0IP0AR20141105}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n{{main|2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election}}\nIn October 2017, Fung announced he would again seek the governorship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wpri.com/2017/10/24/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|work=WPRI 12|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref> He lost in a landslide to [[Gina Raimondo]] by over a fifteen-point margin.\n\n=== Political positions ===\nAllan Fung describes himself as a \"'Rhode Island Republican' -- [[Rockefeller Republican|moderate]], but [[Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/rhode-island-could-elect-its-first-asian-american-governor-n239921|title=Rhode Island Could Elect Its First Asian-American Governor|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/1082427888|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|last=Nunes|first=Rachel|date=2017-10-24|work=WPRI|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> An [[WABC-TV|''Eyewitness News'']] political analyst described Fung as \"a more moderate Republican\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/1082427888|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|last=Nunes|first=Rachel|date=2017-10-24|work=WPRI|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Fung says that he's a [[Pragmatism|pragmatist]] and described  himself as a [[Centrism|centrist]] who promotes bipartisanship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ripr.org/post/cranston-mayor-allan-fung-announces-his-run-governor#stream/0|title=Cranston Mayor Allan Fung Announces His Run For Governor|last=Donnis|first=Ian|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Fiscal policy ====\nFung identifies as fiscally conservative, and rarely had to raise taxes as the mayor of Cranston.<ref name=\":0\" /> Running for Governor, he pledged to cut the sales tax rate in Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.630wpro.com/2014/10/15/news-allan-fung-announces-plan-to-cut-sales-tax-rate/|title=NEWS: Allan Fung announces plan to cut sales tax rate|date=2014-10-15|work=WPRO|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> During a primary debate, he said he supported making Rhode Island a \"[[Right-to-work law|Right-to-work]]\" state and noted that he switched some city employees from a public pension to private plans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/fung-block-butt-heads-televised-gop-debate#stream/0|title=Fung, Block butt heads in televised GOP debate|last=MacKay|first=Scott|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> During the 2018 gubernatorial campaign, Fung proposed reducing the sales tax to five percent, cutting fees, and introducing a concierge service for businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/fung-proposes-cutting-sales-tax-lowering-fees-adding-concierge-business#stream/0|title=Fung Proposes Cutting Sales Tax, Lowering Fees & Adding Concierge For Business|last=Donnis|first=Ian|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> His proposed budget for Cranston in 2018 did not include a tax increase.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/fung-budget-holds-line-on-tax-rate-boosts-spending-44m,132890|title=Taxes stay flat; spending up $4.4M|work=Cranston Herald|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Fung criticized giving health care subsidies to certain corporations calling such a plan \"corporate welfare\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180727/fung-slams-raimondo-over-corporate-welfare-deals-but-wont-say-what-hed-do|title=Fung slams Raimondo over 'corporate welfare deals,' but won't say what he'd do|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref> A\n\nFor funding education, Fung supports charter schools and wants to increase funding for technical education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/fung-talks-about-upcoming-campaign-for-governor,129099|title=Fung opens up about upcoming campaign for Governor|work=Cranston Herald|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Social policy ====\nFung described himself as [[Abortion-rights movements|pro-choice]] on the issue of abortion, but says he is not extreme and supports \"common sense restrictions, such as his opposition to late-term abortion\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/article/20141002/NEWS/310029984|title=As abortion becomes issue in campaign for governor, Fung explains his stance|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He was endorsed by Rhode Island Right to Life, a [[Anti-abortion movements|pro-life]] group opposed to legal abortion, because they supported the restrictions proposed by Fung.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oceanstatecurrent.com/longer-twitter/fungs-pro-life-endorsement/|title=Fung\u2019s Pro-Life Endorsement {{!}} The Current-Anchor|website=oceanstatecurrent.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> As Governor, Fung said that he would consider [[Roe v. Wade|''Roe v Wade'']] to be the law of the land and would not change that.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/26632046/gina-raimondo-and-allan-fung-spar-over-abortion-rights-politics|title=Gina Raimondo and Allan Fung Spar Over Abortion Rights Politics|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Fung later said he no longer identified as pro-choice but said he supports a \"woman's right to make medical decisions\" within some limitations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/09/12/bernie-sanders-inspired-challenger-routed-in-rhode-island-gubernatorial-race-pro-trump-candidate-gets-gop-nod.html|title=Bernie Sanders-inspired challenger routed in Rhode Island gubernatorial race; pro-Trump candidate gets GOP nod|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=2018-09-12|work=Fox News|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/candidates-for-rhode-island-governor-snipe-in-1st-debate/2018/09/27/7f09f6ba-c2be-11e8-9451-e878f96be19b_story.html|title=Candidates for Rhode Island governor snipe in 1st debate|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> In 2018, Fung had this to say about abortion: \"I have always respected a woman\u2019s right to make a medical decision, but with common sense limitations that many of us can agree upon, including a ban on the disgusting practice of late term abortions, having the option of a plan on the healthcare exchange that does not include abortion coverage, and parental notification for minors\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180504/womens-groups-push-back-at-mattiello-on-abortion|title=Women's groups push back at Mattiello on abortion|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.630wpro.com/2018/07/09/raimondo-fung-trade-barbs-on-abortion-protections/|title=Raimondo, Fung trade barbs on abortion protections|date=2018-07-09|work=WPRO|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Fung did not take a position on Rhode Island's Reproductive Health Care Act which would define access to abortion as a right in the state; Fung said he would \"politely decline to comment\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180628/where-they-stand-candidates-on-reproductive-health-care-act|title=Where they stand: the candidates on the Reproductive Health Care Act|last=Dunn|first=Christine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en}}</ref> In 2019, Fung endorsed a pro-choice Republican, Rebecca Schiff, who was running to be the state GOP chairwoman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190321/ri-gop-lawmakers-endorse-3-for-party-chairman|title=R.I. GOP lawmakers endorse 3 for party chairman|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190401/cranston-mayors-wife-resigns-from-republican-committee-over-new-chairwoman|title=Cranston mayor's wife resigns from Republican committee over new chairwoman|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn gay and lesbian rights, Fung has a mixed position. As the Cranston mayor, Fung said \"he's for [[civil union]]s but not same sex marriage\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/21789618/local-mayors-come-out-in-favor-of-gay-marriage|title=Local mayors come out in favor of gay marriage|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) gave Fung a 93% score based on his agreement with their positions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/112969/allan-fung#.Wz_oLtJKiUk|title=Allan Fung's Ratings and Endorsements|last=|first=|date=|website=votesmart.org|access-date=}}</ref> He was endorsed by the NRA for Governor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/26479518/national-rifle-association-endorses-allan-fung-for-governor|title=National Rifle Association Endorses Allan Fung for Governor|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, he opposed Rhode Island's \"red flag\" gun control executive order signed by the Governor because it did not require input from mental health professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/public-justice-safety/tns-raimondo-guns-executive-order.html|title=Rhode Island Governor Signs Executive Order on Guns|website=www.governing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> The NRA was one of his top donors in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/campaign-finance/112969/allan-fung#.W24f4-hKiUk|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Fung opposed President Donald Trump's [[Trump travel ban|travel ban]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170129/cranston-republican-mayor-allan-fung-assails-trump-immigration-order|title=Cranston Republican Mayor Allan Fung assails Trump immigration order|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He supports [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|DACA]] and asked Cranston's city council to approve a resolution supporting his stance in favor of DACA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/scott-mackay-commentary-raimondo-immigrants-and-road-signs#stream/0|title=Scott MacKay Commentary: Of Raimondo, Immigrants And Road Signs|last=MacKay|first=Scott|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He supported [[Marco Rubio]]'s proposal for comprehensive immigration reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianfortunenews.com/2013/10/mayor-allan-fung-climbs-ladder-of-success/|title=Mayor Allan Fung Climbs Ladder of Success {{!}} Asian Fortune|website=www.asianfortunenews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref> The [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] bill would have enhanced border security and given a pathway to legal status and citizenship for undocumented immigrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/gop-primaries/268525-rubio-defends-gang-of-eight-immigration-bill|title=Rubio defends Gang of Eight immigration bill|last=Smilowitz|first=Elliot|date=2016-02-06|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-07-29|language=en}}</ref> Fung opposes issuing drivers' licenses to undocumented immigrants.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also opposes [[sanctuary cities]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180810/gubernatorial-candidate-fung-we-will-not-be-sanctuary-state|title=Gubernatorial candidate Fung: 'We will not be a sanctuary state'|last=Anderson|first=Patrick|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\">{{cite news|last1=Puna|first1=Alisha|title=Cranston\u2019s first family: Mayor Fung and wife Barbara Ann Fenton keep competitive edge to family fun|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170518/cranstons-first-family-mayor-fung-and-wife-barbara-ann-fenton-keep-competitive-edge-to-family-fun|accessdate=22 May 2017|publisher=The Providence Journal|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cranstonri.com/ City of Cranston's website]\n* [http://www.allanfung.com/ Campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Robitaille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=[[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014]], [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fung, Allan}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American mayors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Cranston, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island city council members]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island College alumni]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island Republicans]]\n[[Category:Suffolk University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2014 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Allan Fung\n|image       = Allan Fung.jpg\n|office      = Mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]]\n|term_start  = January 5, 2009\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Michael Napolitano]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Allan Wai-Ket Fung\n|native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hant|\u99ae\u5049\u5091}}}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1970|2|25}}\n|birth_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Barbara Ann Fenton\n|education   = [[Rhode Island College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[Suffolk University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n'''Allan Wai-Ket Fung''' (born February 25, 1970) is an American attorney and politician who has been mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island]], since 2009. He was the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Rhode Island]] in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]] and [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018 election]].\n\nElected mayor in 2008, Fung became the first mayor of Chinese ancestry in Rhode Island. Fung was previously a state prosecutor and attorney on legislative and regulatory affairs before serving on the Cranston City Council as a citywide councilman.\n\nHe lost the gubernatorial race in Rhode Island during 2014 to Democrat [[Gina Raimondo]] by five points and again lost in a landslide to Governor Raimondo in 2018 by over a fifteen-point margin.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nAllan W. Fung ({{zh|t=\u99ae\u5049\u5091}}), born on February 25, 1970, at [[Providence Lying-In Hospital]] (now known as [[Women & Infants Hospital]]), Fung is the eldest of Kwong Wen and Tan Ping's three children. [[Crown colony]] Chinese immigrants from [[British Hong Kong]], his family settled in Rhode Island in 1969, and ran a small business on Cranston Street and Gansett Avenue, Cranston, RI.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cowart|first=Jen|title=Family Fundamental to Fung's career|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/Family-fundamental-to-Fungs-career,87554|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Cranston Herald|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nFung graduated from [[Classical High School]] in Providence, RI in 1988, in the same class as future Providence mayor [[Angel Taveras]]. He earned a B.A. from [[Rhode Island College]] in 1992. He received a Juris Doctor (J.D.) law degree from [[Suffolk University]] Law School in 1995. He received the Classical High School Distinguished Alumni Award in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Distinguished Alumni Awards|url=http://classicalalumni.org/alumni-awards-bios-2009.php|publisher=Classical High School Alumni Association|accessdate=22 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523012705/http://classicalalumni.org/alumni-awards-bios-2009.php|archive-date=2014-05-23|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nFung met Barbara Ann Fenton, a physical therapist, at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]].<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> They married in summer 2016.<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> Fung converted to Catholicism before the wedding.<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\" /> Fung remains a devoted multicultural American with experience in both religious Americana, and United States diversity culture.\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Mayor Fung and Olivia Culpa, Miss USA 2012.jpg|thumb|Fung honors Cranston resident [[Olivia Culpo]] with a key to the City, after her coronation as [[Miss USA 2012]].]]\n[[File:Cranston mayor Allan Fung July 4 2016.jpg|thumb|Fung marched in the 2016 [[Bristol Fourth of July Parade]] with his wife Barbara Ann Fenton.]]\n\nPrior to his municipal leadership career, from 1999 to 2001, Fung served as a prosecutor, acting as Special Assistant, for the Rhode Island Attorney General.<ref>http://www.linkedin.com/in/afung1</ref> Fung served from 2001 to 2009 as the government relations counsel for Metropolitan Life Insurance Company [[MetLife]]. In 2003, he was elected to the Cranston, RI City Council. In 2004, Fung was honored as a Rhode Island Bar Foundation Fellow. He was also a [[Providence Business News]] 40 Under Forty honoree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbn.com/RI-voters-overwhelmingly-OK-bondsbr-re-elect-Kennedy-Langevin-and-Reed-,36144?print=1|title=R.I. voters overwhelmingly OK bonds, re-elect Kennedy, Langevin and Reed - Providence Business News|work=Providence Business News|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407101949/http://www.pbn.com/RI-voters-overwhelmingly-OK-bondsbr-re-elect-Kennedy-Langevin-and-Reed-,36144?print=1|archive-date=7 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Fung was chairman of the Rhode Island Governor's Insurance Council from 2005 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warwick.uber.matchbin.com/printer_friendly/2510188|title='Classical act' honors new mayor|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he was elected mayor in November 2008, beating [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Cynthia M. Fogarty by 63% to 37%. He is the first [[Chinese American]] elected as mayor in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelapa.com/2009/01/allan-fung-rhode-island-first-asian.html|title=Mayor Fung sworn in Monday night|date=5 January 2009|work=WPRI|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slanteyefortheroundeye.com/2009/01/go-go-mayer-allan-fong.html|title=Slant Eye For The Round Eye: Go Go Mayer Allan Fong|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> He succeeded [[Michael Napolitano]], who defeated him for the position in the 2006 election by 79 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/local_wpri_cranston_mayoral_race_20081029|title=Fung wins Cranston's mayoral race|work=WPRI|accessdate=17 November 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130209130248/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/local_wpri_cranston_mayoral_race_20081029|archive-date=2013-02-09|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.providencejournal.com/politics/2006/12/ri-gop-starts-s.html|title=RI GOP starts search for new leader|date=20 December 2006|work=Providence Journal|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> Fung was re-elected in 2010 against Richard R. Tomlins by 76% to 24% and in 2012 against only write-in opponents by 97% to 3%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cranstononline.com/stories/Dems-come-on-strong,76534?category_id=4&town_id=3&sub_type=stories|title=Dems come on strong|last=Fraser|first=Meg|date=7 November 2012|work=Cranston Herald|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> Fung is a council member for the [[Republican National Committee]]'s Asian Pacific American Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asianrepublicans.ning.com|title=THE ASIAN REPUBLICAN NETWORK - Network of Asian Republicans|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625004814/http://asianrepublicans.ning.com/|archive-date=2014-06-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gop.com/general/rnc-launches-national-advisory-councils/|title=RNC Launches National Advisory Councils - GOP|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Edgar|first=Randall|title=Fung Named to RNC Asian American Pacific Advisory Council|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140305-fung-named-to-rnc-asian-pacific-american-advisory-council.ece|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Providence Journal|date=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFung won re-election to a fourth term as Cranston mayor in November 2016, by a landslide ratio of 2 to 1.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Gregory|title=Cranston Mayor Allan W. Fung wins reelection in a landslide|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20161108/cranston-mayor-allan-w-fung-wins-reelection-in-landslide|accessdate=18 November 2016|publisher=The Providence Journal|date=8 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder Fung's leadership, Cranston became one of the Top 50 Cities to Live in America for three years in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/for-third-year-cranston-makes-list-of-50-best-cities,119249|title=For third year, Cranston makes list of '50 Best Cities'|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>  Cranston was also named one of the Top 100 Best Cities to Raise A Child in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alarms.org/best-cities-to-raise-kids-2017/|title=Best Cities to Raise Kids, 2017 - National Council For Home Safety and Security|website=www.alarms.org|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gubernatorial campaigns===\n\n====2014====\n[[File:Mayor Allan Fung visits Providence (cropped).jpg|thumb|Fung in 2014]]\n{{main|2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election}}\nIn November 2013, Fung announced his candidacy for [[Governor of Rhode Island]] in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://woonsocket.patch.com/groups/elections/p/mayor-fung-announces-bid-for-governor-woonsocket|title=Mayor Fung Announces Bid For Governor|date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=November 4, 2013|work=Woonsocket Patch|author=Rob Borkowski|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105155908/http://woonsocket.patch.com/groups/elections/p/mayor-fung-announces-bid-for-governor-woonsocket|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Allan Fung Announces Run for Governor of Rhode Island|url=http://www.8asians.com/2013/11/20/allan-fung-announces-run-for-governor-of-rhode-island/|work=8 Asians|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Howell|first=John|title=Fung stresses jobs in bid for Governor|url=http://www.cranstononline.com/stories/Fung-stresses-jobs-in-bid-for-governor,87133|accessdate=4 December 2013|newspaper=Cranston Herald|date=6 November 2013}}</ref> He received several high-profile Republican endorsements during the campaign, including former Rhode Island Governor [[Lincoln Almond]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edgar|first1=Randall|title=Former governor Lincoln Almond endorses Fung in governor\u2019s race|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140528-former-governor-lincoln-almond-endorses-fung-in-governors-race.ece|accessdate=13 September 2014|publisher=Providence Journal|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> former [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts Governor]] and 2012 presidential nominee [[Mitt Romney]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fowler|first1=Jack|title=Romney Supports Fung|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/387241/romney-supports-fung-jack-fowler|accessdate=13 September 2014|publisher=National Review|date=5 September 2014}}</ref> and former Massachusetts Governor [[William Weld]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Weld Endorses Fung for Governor|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/politics/weld-endorses-fung-for-governor|website=GoLocalProv.com|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> On September 9, 2014, Fung defeated [[Ken Block (politician)|Ken Block]] in the Republican primary, with a 55% majority.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kittridge|first1=Dan|title=Fung wins GOP primary|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/Fung-wins-GOP-primary,95933|accessdate=11 September 2014|agency=Cranston Herald|publisher=Beacon Communications|date=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Schieldrop|first1=Mark|title=Fung wins GOP Nomination for Governor|url=http://patch.com/rhode-island/cranston/fung-wins-gop-nomination-governor-0#.VBSnwi5dUbo|website=Cranston Patch|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Edgar|first1=Randall|last2=Bogdan|first2=Jennifer|title=Cranston's Mayor Fung clinches hard-fought GOP race over Block|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140909-cranstons-mayor-fung-clinches-hard-fought-gop-governors-primary-over-businessman-video.ece|accessdate=14 September 2014|publisher=Providence Journal|date=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914073329/http://www.providencejournal.com/politics/content/20140909-cranstons-mayor-fung-clinches-hard-fought-gop-governors-primary-over-businessman-video.ece|archive-date=2014-09-14|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Statewide Primary|url=http://www.ri.gov/election/results/2014/statewide_primary/|website=RI.gov|publisher=State of Rhode Island Board of Elections|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Soon thereafter, the [[Republican Governors Association]] President also endorsed him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/10/19/fung-republicans-see-opening-governor-race/4dBrGPRtMb2vbL4vrGhSOM/story.html|title=Fung, Republicans see opening in governor\u2019s race - The Boston Globe|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://johnstonsunrise.net/stories/In-Johnston-Christie-touts-Fungs-odds-in-race-for-governor,97017|title=In Johnston, Christie touts Fung\u2019s odds in race for governor|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref> Democrat [[Gina Raimondo]] would go on to win the three-way contest by a 4-point margin.<ref>{{cite web|last=HERBST-BAYLISS|first=SVEA|agency=Reuters|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|accessdate=November 4, 2014|url=\nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/05/us-usa-elections-rhodeisland-governor-idUSKBN0IP0AR20141105}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n{{main|2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election}}\nIn October 2017, Fung announced he would again seek the governorship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wpri.com/2017/10/24/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|work=WPRI 12|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref> He lost in a landslide to [[Gina Raimondo]] by over a fifteen-point margin.\n\n=== Political positions ===\nAllan Fung describes himself as a \"'Rhode Island Republican' -- [[Rockefeller Republican|moderate]], but [[Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/rhode-island-could-elect-its-first-asian-american-governor-n239921|title=Rhode Island Could Elect Its First Asian-American Governor|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/1082427888|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|last=Nunes|first=Rachel|date=2017-10-24|work=WPRI|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> An [[WABC-TV|''Eyewitness News'']] political analyst described Fung as \"a more moderate Republican\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/fung-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/1082427888|title=Fung announces candidacy for governor|last=Nunes|first=Rachel|date=2017-10-24|work=WPRI|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Fung says that he's a [[Pragmatism|pragmatist]] and described  himself as a [[Centrism|centrist]] who promotes bipartisanship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ripr.org/post/cranston-mayor-allan-fung-announces-his-run-governor#stream/0|title=Cranston Mayor Allan Fung Announces His Run For Governor|last=Donnis|first=Ian|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Fiscal policy ====\nFung identifies as fiscally conservative, but defended his decision to raise taxes as the mayor of Cranston.<ref name=\":0\" /> Running for Governor, he pledged to cut the sales tax rate in Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.630wpro.com/2014/10/15/news-allan-fung-announces-plan-to-cut-sales-tax-rate/|title=NEWS: Allan Fung announces plan to cut sales tax rate|date=2014-10-15|work=WPRO|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> During a primary debate, he said he supported making Rhode Island a \"[[Right-to-work law|Right-to-work]]\" state and noted that he switched some city employees from a public pension to private plans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/fung-block-butt-heads-televised-gop-debate#stream/0|title=Fung, Block butt heads in televised GOP debate|last=MacKay|first=Scott|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> During the 2018 gubernatorial campaign, Fung proposed reducing the sales tax to five percent, cutting fees, and introducing a concierge service for businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/fung-proposes-cutting-sales-tax-lowering-fees-adding-concierge-business#stream/0|title=Fung Proposes Cutting Sales Tax, Lowering Fees & Adding Concierge For Business|last=Donnis|first=Ian|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> His proposed budget for Cranston in 2018 did not include a tax increase.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/fung-budget-holds-line-on-tax-rate-boosts-spending-44m,132890|title=Taxes stay flat; spending up $4.4M|work=Cranston Herald|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Fung criticized giving health care subsidies to certain corporations calling such a plan \"corporate welfare\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180727/fung-slams-raimondo-over-corporate-welfare-deals-but-wont-say-what-hed-do|title=Fung slams Raimondo over 'corporate welfare deals,' but won't say what he'd do|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref> Also in 2018, Fung did support increasing city spending by $4.4 million; in 2017 he had supported a 2.2% tax increase.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180330/cranston-mayor-fungs-spending-plan-calls-for-44m-hike|title=Cranston Mayor Fung's spending plan calls for $4.4M hike|last=Parker|first=Paul Edward|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFor funding education, Fung supports charter schools and wants to increase funding for technical education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cranstononline.com/stories/fung-talks-about-upcoming-campaign-for-governor,129099|title=Fung opens up about upcoming campaign for Governor|work=Cranston Herald|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Social policy ====\nFung described himself as [[Abortion-rights movements|pro-choice]] on the issue of abortion, but says he is not extreme and supports \"common sense restrictions, such as his opposition to late-term abortion\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/article/20141002/NEWS/310029984|title=As abortion becomes issue in campaign for governor, Fung explains his stance|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He was endorsed by Rhode Island Right to Life, a [[Anti-abortion movements|pro-life]] group opposed to legal abortion, because they supported the restrictions proposed by Fung.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oceanstatecurrent.com/longer-twitter/fungs-pro-life-endorsement/|title=Fung\u2019s Pro-Life Endorsement {{!}} The Current-Anchor|website=oceanstatecurrent.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> As Governor, Fung said that he would consider [[Roe v. Wade|''Roe v Wade'']] to be the law of the land and would not change that.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/26632046/gina-raimondo-and-allan-fung-spar-over-abortion-rights-politics|title=Gina Raimondo and Allan Fung Spar Over Abortion Rights Politics|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Fung later said he no longer identified as pro-choice but said he supports a \"woman's right to make medical decisions\" within some limitations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/09/12/bernie-sanders-inspired-challenger-routed-in-rhode-island-gubernatorial-race-pro-trump-candidate-gets-gop-nod.html|title=Bernie Sanders-inspired challenger routed in Rhode Island gubernatorial race; pro-Trump candidate gets GOP nod|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=2018-09-12|work=Fox News|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/candidates-for-rhode-island-governor-snipe-in-1st-debate/2018/09/27/7f09f6ba-c2be-11e8-9451-e878f96be19b_story.html|title=Candidates for Rhode Island governor snipe in 1st debate|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> In 2018, Fung had this to say about abortion: \"I have always respected a woman\u2019s right to make a medical decision, but with common sense limitations that many of us can agree upon, including a ban on the disgusting practice of late term abortions, having the option of a plan on the healthcare exchange that does not include abortion coverage, and parental notification for minors\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180504/womens-groups-push-back-at-mattiello-on-abortion|title=Women's groups push back at Mattiello on abortion|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.630wpro.com/2018/07/09/raimondo-fung-trade-barbs-on-abortion-protections/|title=Raimondo, Fung trade barbs on abortion protections|date=2018-07-09|work=WPRO|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Fung did not take a position on Rhode Island's Reproductive Health Care Act which would define access to abortion as a right in the state; Fung said he would \"politely decline to comment\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180628/where-they-stand-candidates-on-reproductive-health-care-act|title=Where they stand: the candidates on the Reproductive Health Care Act|last=Dunn|first=Christine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en}}</ref> In 2019, Fung endorsed a pro-choice Republican, Rebecca Schiff, who was running to be the state GOP chairwoman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190321/ri-gop-lawmakers-endorse-3-for-party-chairman|title=R.I. GOP lawmakers endorse 3 for party chairman|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190401/cranston-mayors-wife-resigns-from-republican-committee-over-new-chairwoman|title=Cranston mayor's wife resigns from Republican committee over new chairwoman|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn gay and lesbian rights, Fung has a mixed position. As the Cranston mayor, Fung said \"he's for [[civil union]]s but not same sex marriage\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/21789618/local-mayors-come-out-in-favor-of-gay-marriage|title=Local mayors come out in favor of gay marriage|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) gave Fung a 93% score based on his agreement with their positions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/112969/allan-fung#.Wz_oLtJKiUk|title=Allan Fung's Ratings and Endorsements|last=|first=|date=|website=votesmart.org|access-date=}}</ref> He was endorsed by the NRA for Governor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc6.com/story/26479518/national-rifle-association-endorses-allan-fung-for-governor|title=National Rifle Association Endorses Allan Fung for Governor|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, he opposed Rhode Island's \"red flag\" gun control executive order signed by the Governor because it did not require input from mental health professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/public-justice-safety/tns-raimondo-guns-executive-order.html|title=Rhode Island Governor Signs Executive Order on Guns|website=www.governing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> The NRA was one of his top donors in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/campaign-finance/112969/allan-fung#.W24f4-hKiUk|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Fung opposed President Donald Trump's [[Trump travel ban|travel ban]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170129/cranston-republican-mayor-allan-fung-assails-trump-immigration-order|title=Cranston Republican Mayor Allan Fung assails Trump immigration order|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He supports [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|DACA]] and asked Cranston's city council to approve a resolution supporting his stance in favor of DACA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ripr.org/post/scott-mackay-commentary-raimondo-immigrants-and-road-signs#stream/0|title=Scott MacKay Commentary: Of Raimondo, Immigrants And Road Signs|last=MacKay|first=Scott|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> He supported [[Marco Rubio]]'s proposal for comprehensive immigration reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianfortunenews.com/2013/10/mayor-allan-fung-climbs-ladder-of-success/|title=Mayor Allan Fung Climbs Ladder of Success {{!}} Asian Fortune|website=www.asianfortunenews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref> The [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] bill would have enhanced border security and given a pathway to legal status and citizenship for undocumented immigrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/gop-primaries/268525-rubio-defends-gang-of-eight-immigration-bill|title=Rubio defends Gang of Eight immigration bill|last=Smilowitz|first=Elliot|date=2016-02-06|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-07-29|language=en}}</ref> Fung opposes issuing drivers' licenses to undocumented immigrants.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also opposes [[sanctuary cities]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180810/gubernatorial-candidate-fung-we-will-not-be-sanctuary-state|title=Gubernatorial candidate Fung: 'We will not be a sanctuary state'|last=Anderson|first=Patrick|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2018-08-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ProJo20170518\">{{cite news|last1=Puna|first1=Alisha|title=Cranston\u2019s first family: Mayor Fung and wife Barbara Ann Fenton keep competitive edge to family fun|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170518/cranstons-first-family-mayor-fung-and-wife-barbara-ann-fenton-keep-competitive-edge-to-family-fun|accessdate=22 May 2017|publisher=The Providence Journal|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cranstonri.com/ City of Cranston's website]\n* [http://www.allanfung.com/ Campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Robitaille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=[[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014]], [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fung, Allan}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American mayors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Cranston, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island city council members]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island College alumni]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island Republicans]]\n[[Category:Suffolk University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2014 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8805:8100:62:95b4:1740:a793:a2fb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFiscal policy)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Fung"}
{"title_page": "Dahapara Dham railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Dahapara Dham railway station\n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang= \n| style           = Indian railway\n| type            = [[Passenger train]] station\n| image           =\n| caption         = \n| address         =  Rajbari, Dahapara, [[Murshidabad district]], [[West Bengal]]\n| country         = [[India]]\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|24.1145|N|88.1444|E|format=dms}}\n| elevation       = {{cvt|21|m}}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Eastern Railway zone]]\n| line            = [[Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa loop]] Line\n| platform        = 2\n| tracks          = 2\n| other           =\n| ADA             = \n| parking         = \n| structure       = Standard (on ground station)\n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = DHPD\n  | zone = [[Eastern Railway zone]]\n  | division = {{rwd|Howrah}}\n  }}\n| status          = Active\n| closed          = \n| former          = [[East Indian Railway Company]]\n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = Yes\n| passengers      = \n| pass_system     = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| services = {{s-rail|title=Indian Railway}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways|previous= Lalbag Court Road|next= Azimganj Junction|line=Eastern Railway zone|branch= [[Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa loop|Azimganj-Katwa line]]|rows1=1}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Dahapara Dham railway station''' is a halt railway station on the [[Barharwa-Azimganj-Katwa Loop Line|Howrah-Azimganj Line]] of [[Howrah railway division]] of [[Eastern Railway zone]]. It is situated at Dahapara village of [[Murshidabad district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/indian-railway/dhapara-dham-dhpd-station|title=DHAPARA DHAM (DHPD) Railway Station|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1913, the Hooghly\u2013Katwa Railway constructed a {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] line from [[Bandel Junction railway station|Bandel]] to [[Katwa Junction railway station|Katwa]], and the Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa Railway constructed the {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] [[Barharwa-Azimganj-Katwa Loop Line]].<ref name=timeline>{{cite web| url = http://irse.bravehost.com/IRHTML.htm| title = Indian Railway History timeline| last = R.P.Saxena| accessdate = 16 April 2019| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120714085533/http://irse.bravehost.com/IRHTML.htm| archivedate = 14 July 2012| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/chronology.html | title = The Chronology of Railway development in Eastern Indian | publisher = railindia | accessdate = 16 April 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316015721/http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/chronology.html | archive-date = 16 March 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref> With the construction of the [[Farakka Barrage]] and opening of the railway bridge in 1971, the railway communication picture of this line were completely changed. Total 11 local trains stop at Dahapara Dham railway station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indiarailinfo.com/station/map/dahapara-dham-dhpd/8023|title=DHPD/Dahapara Dham|publisher=indiarailinfo.com|access-date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Murshidabad district]]\n[[Category:Howrah railway division]]\n\n{{WestBengal-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Dahapara Dham railway station\n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang= \n| style           = Indian railway\n| type            = [[Passenger train]] station\n| image           =\n| caption         = \n| address         =  Rajbari, Dahapara, [[Murshidabad district]], [[West Bengal]]\n| country         = [[India]]\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|24.1145|N|88.1444|E|format=dms}}\n| elevation       = {{cvt|21|m}}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Eastern Railway zone]]\n| line            = [[Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa loop]] Line\n| platform        = 1\n| tracks          = 2\n| other           =\n| ADA             = \n| parking         = \n| structure       = Standard (on ground station)\n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = DHPD\n  | zone = [[Eastern Railway zone]]\n  | division = {{rwd|Howrah}}\n  }}\n| status          = Active\n| closed          = \n| former          = [[East Indian Railway Company]]\n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = Yes\n| passengers      = \n| pass_system     = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| services = {{s-rail|title=Indian Railway}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways|previous= Lalbag Court Road|next= Azimganj Junction|line=Eastern Railway zone|branch= [[Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa loop|Azimganj-Katwa line]]|rows1=1}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Dahapara Dham railway station''' is a halt railway station on the [[Barharwa-Azimganj-Katwa Loop Line|Howrah-Azimganj Line]] of [[Howrah railway division]] of [[Eastern Railway zone]]. It is situated at Dahapara village of [[Murshidabad district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/indian-railway/dhapara-dham-dhpd-station|title=DHAPARA DHAM (DHPD) Railway Station|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1913, the Hooghly\u2013Katwa Railway constructed a {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] line from [[Bandel Junction railway station|Bandel]] to [[Katwa Junction railway station|Katwa]], and the Barharwa\u2013Azimganj\u2013Katwa Railway constructed the {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] [[Barharwa-Azimganj-Katwa Loop Line]].<ref name=timeline>{{cite web| url = http://irse.bravehost.com/IRHTML.htm| title = Indian Railway History timeline| last = R.P.Saxena| accessdate = 16 April 2019| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120714085533/http://irse.bravehost.com/IRHTML.htm| archivedate = 14 July 2012| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/chronology.html | title = The Chronology of Railway development in Eastern Indian | publisher = railindia | accessdate = 16 April 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316015721/http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/chronology.html | archive-date = 16 March 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref> With the construction of the [[Farakka Barrage]] and opening of the railway bridge in 1971, the railway communication picture of this line were completely changed. Total 11 local trains stop at Dahapara Dham railway station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indiarailinfo.com/station/map/dahapara-dham-dhpd/8023|title=DHPD/Dahapara Dham|publisher=indiarailinfo.com|access-date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Murshidabad district]]\n[[Category:Howrah railway division]]\n\n{{WestBengal-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pinakpani", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dahapara_Dham_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Madzikane", "text_new": "{{short description|King of the Bhaca}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=January 2016}}\n{{expert subject|date=October 2010}}\n}}\n\n\n\n'''Madzikane''' was the founder and a king of the [[Bhaca]] people. Before him, his father's tribe was known as Abakwa Zelemu but after Madzikane had united many multitudes of different people and different clans, his nation was known as amaBhaca consisting of many clans including: [[Zulu people|amaZulu]], akwaZelemu, amaWushe, amaNqolo, amaNzelu, amaZizi, amaNjilo, abaseNhlwangini, amaQwabe, abaThembu, etc.\n\n==Family==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2015}}\nMadzikane's father was Khalimesh. His firstborn was Crown Prince Sonyangwe followed by Prince Ncapai. However, because of the [[Mfecane]] wars, Sonyangwe the crown prince was burnt to death at night in his hut by traitors from the Memela who were vassals of the [[Bhele|AmaBhele]] of uMdingi who were subjects of King Madzikane while he still reigned. Prince Sonyangwe died at Rode before he could become King of amaBhaca.\n\nTherefore, on the death of King Madzikane, Prince Ncaphayi was crowned King of all amaBhaca but because his elder brother Sonyangwe had left behind two sons in [[Early history of Natal|Natal]], (i.e. Princes Mdutyane and Thiba), King Ncaphayi was obliged to share the throne with Sonyangwes' heir. When Prince Mdutyane was only twenty-one, King Ncaphayi died in a war against the [[Mpondo people|AmaMpondo]] King Faku. Crown Prince Mdutyane was crowned King of all the amaBhaca tribes and hence became the supreme ruler of the whole amaBhaca nation consisting of more than forty-four different tribes scattered all over southern Natal.\n\n===Wives===\nKing Ncapayi had many wives. Indlu Enkulu birth to Diko and Sogoni. From his second wife, Indlu Ykaula,{{clarify|date=December 2015}}. His third wife Iqadi Lendlu Enkulu bore Dabula. King Madzikane's kingdom is currently being revived by the Reat House of Ncapayi, Inkosi Madzikane II Thandisizwe Diko. The home of the Bhacas and the Kingdom is in [[Mount Frere]], KwaBhaca in the Eastern Cape.\n\nNcapayi is said to have been a fearless freebooter, a diplomat of note who showed even more intelligence than his father and was respected by many nations (Soga, p.&nbsp;444)\n\n===Death===\nAccording to Reverend Soga, during the same year in which Ncapayi\u2019s father Madzikane was killed, Ncaphayi entered [[Tembuland]] to avenge his father\u2019s death. The Thembus under King Ngubengcuka made an ineffectual stand and the Bhacas swept away a large number of cattle.<ref name=\"Soga\">(Soga, p.&nbsp;443)</ref>\n\nBefore King Madzikane died, and because of the relationship he had with King Faku, he advised his son to temporarily be a tributary king in [[Pondoland]]. He indeed did that and Faku at this time welcomed the Bhacas as this also coincided with the arrival of Nqetho, a chief of the Qwabes who had moved from Natal running away from King Tshaka\u2019s army because he could not serve under King [[Dingane kaSenzangakhona|Dingane]]. When he entered Pondoland and tried to secure land by violence, Faku was anxious to get rid of him and therefore secured assistance from Ncaphayi to eject Nqetho. amaBhaca drove them back into Natal and Dingane issued instructions to kill Nqetho.<ref name=\"Soga\" />\n\nSoon after Sonyangwe's death King Madzikane died, but before he died he split the Kingdom of the Bhacas between his deceased crown prince and his son Prince Ncaphayi.\n\nThe Thembus defeat by the Bhacas, also led to Faku making an arrangement with Ncapayi when Pondos wanted to attack the Thembus. They entered Thembuland on three successive occasions and each time their raid was a success.\n\nSoga asserts that [[greed|cupidity]] is said to have been the force that brought Faku and Ncapayi to work together. It is also cupidity that is said to have destroyed their good working relationship. Because they were both strong, it  became difficult to know which one was more powerful than the other. Ncapayi attacked Nyanda, the right hand section of the Phondos under Ndamase, the son of [[Faku a Ngqungqushe|Faku]]. He raided Nyanda successfully. Meanwhile, the alarm had been raised with Faku and he Faku assembled a powerful army and this came up with the Bhacas and attacked them on all sides. Faku drove the Bhacas before him onto the kuNowalala Ridge. Ncaphayi was wounded and forced over the edge, falling onto a ledge some distance from the bottom. He was in helpless condition with both arms broken, besides a severe [[assegai]] (spear) wound. He lay there for days, persuading those who came to look at him to put an end to his misery and kill him. No one could do this until Faku gave orders that he must be killed. Madzikane\u2019s son, King Ncapayi died in 1845.\n\n=Ncapai=\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = Ncapai ka Madzikane\n| birth_date  = c. 1804\n| birth_place = Bluff (Esibubulungu) now\n[[Durban]] [[Zulu Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = {{death year and age|1846|1804}}\n| death_place = Nowalala, [[Pondoland]] \n| title       = King of [[AmaBhaca]] Kingdom\n| predecessor  = Sonyangwe ka Madzikane\n| successor   = Diko ka Ncapai\n| spouse      = Makhohlisa (senior wife) and several other wives\n\n}}\n\n'''Ncapai''' (also spelt as Ncapayi or Ncaphayi) was the king of the Bhaca people between 1826 until his death in 1846. He was the second son from the first wife of King Madzikane ka Zulu. The first born being Sonyangwe his elder brother. He resided at his father's royal residence in Mpoza great place facing Mganu mountains and also build another residence in the nearby Lutateni. <ref name=\"Soga\">(Soga, p.&nbsp;443)</ref> While trying to attack mpondo people due to Maitland treaty he fell off the cliff  died in a place called Nowalala near Ntabankulu in March 1844. Faku ordered he must be killed to save him from pain and agony he had suffered as for days he had plunged beneath the cliff. <ref name=\"Hammond-Tooke, W.D.\">(Hammond-Tooke, W.D, p.&nbsp;34 - 37)</ref> Ncapayi is said to have been a ruthless freebooter <ref name=\"George McCall Theal\">(George McCall Theal,History of South Africa from 1873 to 1884 p.&nbsp;37)</ref>.\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Sonyangwe kaMadzikane]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[King of the Bhaca Nation]] | years=1826\u20131846}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Diko ka Ncapai ]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n==1837==\nIn about 1837, [[Boer]]s arrived in Natal with herds of cattle and the Bhacas saw an opportunity to attack and raid. Between 1837 and 1840, the Bhacas teamed up with the Bushmen and raided the Boers.\n\n==1838==\nIn about February 1838, the Boers settled in the upland of Natal and had successfully set the foundation upon which they could build the [[Natalia Republic|Republic of Natalia]]. After their victories over Dingane, they extended northward to uMfolozi and St. Lucia Bay (Blue Book on Native Affairs, 1885). The Boers had managed to make arrangements with other kings and therefore no longer considered them as potential enemies. For example, they considered King Faku a friendly king and rated Ncapayi a threat as he had a powerful military.\n\nWhen the Boers returned, they decided to attack the [[Bhaca people|Bhacas]] (Bryant, p.&nbsp;400) and raided with 700 men and 50 horses (Nchanga, 119). This is said to have provided the spark for the British intervention in the Bhaca land. (At this time this land had become part of Natal). There is an area near the town of Maclear which is still called Ncapayi land (Kapayi land \u2013 because they could not pronounce \u201cNca\u201d).\n\n==1845==\nBy 1845 the Bhacas had already been stripped of their Kingdom by the  Maitland Treaty. Ncapayi, the first enemy in the Maitland Treaty died and was survived by his first son Diko. But he would be reduced to a headman later on.\n\nINkosi Diko was a hero, a stubborn and a fearless leader of courage. He led the amaBhaca nation for thirty-five years from 1845 to 1880 after the death of his father iKumkani Ncapayi ka Madzikane. INkosi Diko was the grandson of King Madzikane ka Zulu.\n\n==1880==\niNkosi Diko was a fierce leader who fought against the [[annexation]] of the land by the British colonial government. He resisted handing over the AmaBhaca nation so its people could become British subjects. As a result of his resistance to the oppressive rule of the colonisers he was not a favourite of the colonial government of his time. The government decided to overthrow him in 1880. The oppression of Diko\u2019s house had been felt by all eight generations, for a period of 130 years.\n\nAccording to the writings of Anderson Mhlawuli Makaula (1988), by virtue of birth, and according to tradition, Diko was the heir to iKumkani Ncaphayi. But because some of the councillors of AmaBhaca liked Mamjucu, the mother of Makaula, she was fraudulently made a great wife, hence her son attained chieftainship. Makhohlisa (the mother of Diko and Sogoni) who was Ncaphayi\u2019s wife of the great house (uNdlunkulu), was not loved by these councillors, hence they plotted against her.\n\nIt happened that Ncaphayi had killed a man in one of the Mfecane battles and according to AmaBhaca tradition, iNkosi was not supposed to have any contact with his wives until he had undergone some medical treatment. A separate accommodation was to be provided for him. Ncaphayi was then placed in isolation for a stipulated period. The councillors under Qulu Siwela further conspired so that the wife who goes to cook for iNkosi Ncaphayi while he is in isolation, and conceives during that period, would be the one who would give birth to the chief that would succeed him after his death.\n\nThe councillors first went to uNdlunkulu Makhohlisa (Diko and Sogoni\u2019s mother) and deceived her. They told her that she must not dare put her foot in the isolation room where Ncaphayi was sleeping, because this would weaken her sons and cause death by assegai among her children. This sounded reasonable to Makhohlisa. Thereafter the same councillors went to advise Mamjucu (the second wife) to go and cook for iNkosi Ncaphayi in the isolation place. She acted as instructed and her son Makaula was then made iNkosi of AmaBhaca.\n\nSince then, because of this conspiracy of trickery and treachery, the Great House of Ncaphayi has suffered a great deal of disrespect, degradation, and injustice throughout generations that followed.\n\nAfter iNkosi Ncaphayi\u2019s death, Diko (his first and eldest son) led amaBhaca from 1845. iNkosi Diko was always in conflict with the British government and he blatantly refused the annexation of the amaBhaca nation's land. When the British supremacy pervaded the [[Transkei]] Territory during the 1860s, the government pioneered the annexation of the Transkeian Territories. The amakhosi were to give up their power and become subjects of the British Colonial Government. Magistrates were to take over power from the amaKhosi, especially those who refused to submit their nations to be under British rule. iNkosi Diko was one of those traditional leaders who resisted and he was then overthrown, deposed, and made headman by the Colonial Government in 1880.\n\nBattles were fought throughout this period. For example, a friend to iNkosi Diko was iNkosi Mhlontlo of amaMpondomise who is said to have killed a magistrate at [[Qumbu]] while resisting annexation. Other amaKhosi who accepted annexation were rewarded for their loyalty to the colonial government and were looked after and treated well.\n\nThe plan to destroy any trace of iNkosi Diko and his descendants has prevailed over generations after this great hero had died. Even today, Diko\u2019s files, from iNkosi Diko himself, Qoza ka-Diko, Mthakathi ka-Qoza, Mabhijela ka-Mthakathi, Dingumhlaba ka-Mabhijela and Mzawugugi ka-Dingumhlaba (all the descendants of Diko) have been removed from the archives in [[Mthatha]]. The big question is: What happened to these files and where are they?\n                                       \nAmaBhaca are mainly found in the small towns such as Mount Frere, [[Umzimkhulu|uMzimkhulu]], Xopo and some surrounding areas. The isiBhaca language is a mixture of [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]], [[isiZulu]] and [[Swazi language|isiSwati]]. The language of isiSwati was influenced by the fact that King Madzikane\u2019s mother was from one of the Royal Houses of the Swatis of aMalambo. He grew up within the Swatis from his mother\u2019s side and therefore spoke the language. Although he accepts that he is not an authority on this, Jordan, A.C. (1953) argues and also asserts that in the traditional history of the Bhacas, \u201cuDlamini and kwaDlamini\u201d figure a great deal (P.5). He further states that the Bhaca language was stifled to death chiefly by isiXhasa through, amongst others, schools and churches and that a large number of enlightened Bhacas were taught to look down upon their mother tongue.\n\nDiko is the first son of Ncapayi, (Makhohlisa a daughter of Dzanibe clan was the first wife of Ncapayi) with his younger brother Sogoni from the first wife of Ncaphayi. The younger brother from the second wife was Inkosi Makaula followed by Inkosi Dabula and others from other younger wives. Inkosi Madzikane ll Diko is the crown prince of iNkosi Dilizintaba, ka Dingumhlaba, ka Mabhijela i, ka  kaMthakathi, kaQoza ka Diko ka Ncaphayi, ka Madzikane, ka Khalimeshe, ka Vebi, ka Wabane, ka Didi, ka Zulu, ka Ntombela, ka Malandela, ka Dlungwana, ka Ndaba.\n\nINkosi Madzikane II Thandisizwe Diko is currently the head of the kwaBhaca/LuBhacweni Traditional Council at ELundzini Royal Kraal, Ncunteni Great Place, LuBhacweni A/A in Mount Frere, KwaBhaca.\n\nAmaBhaca were therefore stripped off their dignity and their Kingdomship by the colonial powers, the Boers, the [[Griqua people|Griquas]] and later on, the [[apartheid]]  did not make it any better. The home of the Bhacas is in Mount Frere, while other Bhacas who went back to KwaZulu are in Mzimkhulu and Ixopo under the Zulu Kingdom.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Bhaca kings]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bhaca.co.za Bhaca| AmaBhaca]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:19th-century monarchs in Africa]]\n[[Category:South African chiefs]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of South Africa]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-royal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|King of the Bhaca}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=January 2016}}\n{{expert subject|date=October 2010}}\n}}\n\n\n\n'''Madzikane''' was the founder and a king of the [[Bhaca]] people. Before him, his father's tribe was known as Abakwa Zelemu but after Madzikane had united many multitudes of different people and different clans, his nation was known as amaBhaca consisting of many clans including: [[Zulu people|amaZulu]], akwaZelemu, amaWushe, amaNqolo, amaNzelu, amaZizi, amaNjilo, abaseNhlwangini, amaQwabe, abaThembu, etc.\n\n==Family==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2015}}\nMadzikane's father was Khalimesh. His firstborn was Crown Prince Sonyangwe followed by Prince Ncapai. However, because of the [[Mfecane]] wars, Sonyangwe the crown prince was burnt to death at night in his hut by traitors from the Memela who were vassals of the [[Bhele|AmaBhele]] of uMdingi who were subjects of King Madzikane while he still reigned. Prince Sonyangwe died at Rode before he could become King of amaBhaca.\n\nTherefore, on the death of King Madzikane, Prince Ncaphayi was crowned King of all amaBhaca but because his elder brother Sonyangwe had left behind two sons in [[Early history of Natal|Natal]], (i.e. Princes Mdutyane and Thiba), King Ncaphayi was obliged to share the throne with Sonyangwes' heir. When Prince Mdutyane was only twenty-one, King Ncaphayi died in a war against the [[Mpondo people|AmaMpondo]] King Faku. Crown Prince Mdutyane was crowned King of all the amaBhaca tribes and hence became the supreme ruler of the whole amaBhaca nation consisting of more than forty-four different tribes scattered all over southern Natal.\n\n===Wives===\nKing Ncapayi had many wives. Indlu Enkulu birth to Diko and Sogoni. From his second wife, Indlu Ykaula,{{clarify|date=December 2015}}. His third wife Iqadi Lendlu Enkulu bore Dabula. King Madzikane's kingdom is currently being revived by the Reat House of Ncapayi, Inkosi Madzikane II Thandisizwe Diko. The home of the Bhacas and the Kingdom is in [[Mount Frere]], KwaBhaca in the Eastern Cape.\n\nNcapayi is said to have been a fearless freebooter, a diplomat of note who showed even more intelligence than his father and was respected by many nations (Soga, p.&nbsp;444)\n\n===Death===\nAccording to Reverend Soga, during the same year in which Ncapayi\u2019s father Madzikane was killed, Ncaphayi entered [[Tembuland]] to avenge his father\u2019s death. The Thembus under King Ngubengcuka made an ineffectual stand and the Bhacas swept away a large number of cattle.<ref name=\"Soga\">(Soga, p.&nbsp;443)</ref>\n\nBefore King Madzikane died, and because of the relationship he had with King Faku, he advised his son to temporarily be a tributary king in [[Pondoland]]. He indeed did that and Faku at this time welcomed the Bhacas as this also coincided with the arrival of Nqetho, a chief of the Qwabes who had moved from Natal running away from King Tshaka\u2019s army because he could not serve under King [[Dingane kaSenzangakhona|Dingane]]. When he entered Pondoland and tried to secure land by violence, Faku was anxious to get rid of him and therefore secured assistance from Ncaphayi to eject Nqetho. amaBhaca drove them back into Natal and Dingane issued instructions to kill Nqetho.<ref name=\"Soga\" />\n\nSoon after Sonyangwe's death King Madzikane died, but before he died he split the Kingdom of the Bhacas between his deceased crown prince and his son Prince Ncaphayi.\n\nThe Thembus defeat by the Bhacas, also led to Faku making an arrangement with Ncapayi when Pondos wanted to attack the Thembus. They entered Thembuland on three successive occasions and each time their raid was a success.\n\nSoga asserts that [[greed|cupidity]] is said to have been the force that brought Faku and Ncapayi to work together. It is also cupidity that is said to have destroyed their good working relationship. Because they were both strong, it  became difficult to know which one was more powerful than the other. Ncapayi attacked Nyanda, the right hand section of the Phondos under Ndamase, the son of [[Faku a Ngqungqushe|Faku]]. He raided Nyanda successfully. Meanwhile, the alarm had been raised with Faku and he Faku assembled a powerful army and this came up with the Bhacas and attacked them on all sides. Faku drove the Bhacas before him onto the kuNowalala Ridge. Ncaphayi was wounded and forced over the edge, falling onto a ledge some distance from the bottom. He was in helpless condition with both arms broken, besides a severe [[assegai]] (spear) wound. He lay there for days, persuading those who came to look at him to put an end to his misery and kill him. No one could do this until Faku gave orders that he must be killed. Madzikane\u2019s son, King Ncapayi died in 1845.\n\n=Ncapai=\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = Ncapai ka Madzikane\n| birth_date  = c. 1804\n| birth_place = Bluff (Esibubulungu) now\n[[Durban]] [[Zulu Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = {{death year and age|1846|1804}}\n| death_place = Nowalala, [[Pondoland]] \n| title       = King of [[AmaBhaca]] Kingdom\n| predecessor  = Sonyangwe ka Madzikane\n| successor   = Diko ka Ncapai\n| spouse      = Makhohlisa (senior wife) and several other wives\n\n}}\n\n'''Ncapai''' (also spelt as Ncapayi or Ncaphayi) was the king of the Bhaca people between 1826 until his death in 1846. He was the second son from the first wife of King Madzikane ka Zulu. The first born being Sonyangwe his elder brother. He resided at his father's royal residence in Mpoza great place facing Mganu mountains and also build another residence in the nearby Lutateni. <ref name=\"Soga\">(Soga, p.&nbsp;443)</ref> While trying to attack mpondo people due to Maitland treaty he fell off the cliff  died in a place called Nowalala near Ntabankulu in March 1844. Faku ordered he must be killed to save him from pain and agony he had suffered as for days he had plunged beneath the cliff. <ref name=\"Hammond-Tooke, W.D.\">(Hammond-Tooke, W.D, p.&nbsp;34 - 37)</ref> Ncapayi is said to have been a ruthless freebooter <ref name=\"George McCall Theal\">(George McCall Theal,History of South Africa from 1873 to 1884 p.&nbsp;37)</ref>.\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Sonyangwe kaMadzikane]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[King of the Bhaca Nation]] | years=1826\u20131846}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Diko ka Ncapai ]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n==1837==\nIn about 1837, [[Boer]]s arrived in Natal with herds of cattle and the Bhacas saw an opportunity to attack and raid. Between 1837 and 1840, the Bhacas teamed up with the Bushmen and raided the Boers.\n\n==1838==\nIn about February 1838, the Boers settled in the upland of Natal and had successfully set the foundation upon which they could build the [[Natalia Republic|Republic of Natalia]]. After their victories over Dingane, they extended northward to uMfolozi and St. Lucia Bay (Blue Book on Native Affairs, 1885). The Boers had managed to make arrangements with other kings and therefore no longer considered them as potential enemies. For example, they considered King Faku a friendly king and rated Ncapayi a threat as he had a powerful military.\n\nWhen the Boers returned, they decided to attack the [[Bhaca people|Bhacas]] (Bryant, p.&nbsp;400) and raided with 700 men and 50 horses (Nchanga, 119). This is said to have provided the spark for the British intervention in the Bhaca land. (At this time this land had become part of Natal). There is an area near the town of Maclear which is still called Ncapayi land (Kapayi land \u2013 because they could not pronounce \u201cNca\u201d).\n\n==1845==\nBy 1845 the Bhacas had already been stripped of their Kingdom by the  Maitland Treaty. Ncapayi, the first enemy in the Maitland Treaty died and was survived by his first son Diko. But he would be reduced to a headman later on.\n\nINkosi Diko was a hero, a stubborn and a fearless leader of courage. He led the amaBhaca nation for thirty-five years from 1845 to 1880 after the death of his father iKumkani Ncapayi ka Madzikane. INkosi Diko was the grandson of King Madzikane ka Zulu.\n\n==1880==\niNkosi Diko was a fierce leader who fought against the [[annexation]] of the land by the British colonial government. He resisted handing over the AmaBhaca nation so its people could become British subjects. As a result of his resistance to the oppressive rule of the colonisers he was not a favourite of the colonial government of his time. The government decided to overthrow him in 1880. The oppression of Diko\u2019s house had been felt by all eight generations, for a period of 130 years.\n\nAccording to the writings of Anderson Mhlawuli Makaula (1988), by virtue of birth, and according to tradition, Diko was the heir to iKumkani Ncaphayi. But because some of the councillors of AmaBhaca liked Mamjucu, the mother of Makaula, she was fraudulently made a great wife, hence her son attained chieftainship. Makhohlisa (the mother of Diko and Sogoni) who was Ncaphayi\u2019s wife of the great house (uNdlunkulu), was not loved by these councillors, hence they plotted against her.\n\nIt happened that Ncaphayi had killed a man in one of the Mfecane battles and according to AmaBhaca tradition, iNkosi was not supposed to have any contact with his wives until he had undergone some medical treatment. A separate accommodation was to be provided for him. Ncaphayi was then placed in isolation for a stipulated period. The councillors under Qulu Siwela further conspired so that the wife who goes to cook for iNkosi Ncaphayi while he is in isolation, and conceives during that period, would be the one who would give birth to the chief that would succeed him after his death.\n\nThe councillors first went to uNdlunkulu Makhohlisa (Diko and Sogoni\u2019s mother) and deceived her. They told her that she must not dare put her foot in the isolation room where Ncaphayi was sleeping, because this would weaken her sons and cause death by assegai among her children. This sounded reasonable to Makhohlisa. Thereafter the same councillors went to advise Mamjucu (the second wife) to go and cook for iNkosi Ncaphayi in the isolation place. She acted as instructed and her son Makaula was then made iNkosi of AmaBhaca.\n\nSince then, because of this conspiracy of trickery and treachery, the Great House of Ncaphayi has suffered a great deal of disrespect, degradation, and injustice throughout generations that followed.\n\nAfter iNkosi Ncaphayi\u2019s death, Diko (his first and eldest son) led amaBhaca from 1845. iNkosi Diko was always in conflict with the British government and he blatantly refused the annexation of the amaBhaca nation's land. When the British supremacy pervaded the [[Transkei]] Territory during the 1860s, the government pioneered the annexation of the Transkeian Territories. The amakhosi were to give up their power and become subjects of the British Colonial Government. Magistrates were to take over power from the amaKhosi, especially those who refused to submit their nations to be under British rule. iNkosi Diko was one of those traditional leaders who resisted and he was then overthrown, deposed, and made headman by the Colonial Government in 1880.\n\nBattles were fought throughout this period. For example, a friend to iNkosi Diko was iNkosi Mhlontlo of amaMpondomise who is said to have killed a magistrate at [[Qumbu]] while resisting annexation. Other amaKhosi who accepted annexation were rewarded for their loyalty to the colonial government and were looked after and treated well.\n\nThe plan to destroy any trace of iNkosi Diko and his descendants has prevailed over generations after this great hero had died. Even today, Diko\u2019s files, from iNkosi Diko himself, Qoza ka-Diko, Mthakathi ka-Qoza, Mabhijela ka-Mthakathi, Dingumhlaba ka-Mabhijela and Mzawugugi ka-Dingumhlaba (all the descendants of Diko) have been removed from the archives in [[Mthatha]]. The big question is: What happened to these files and where are they?\n                                       \nAmaBhaca are mainly found in the small towns such as Mount Frere, [[Umzimkhulu|uMzimkhulu]], Xopo and some surrounding areas. The isiBhaca language is a mixture of [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]], [[isiZulu]] and [[Swazi language|isiSwati]]. The language of isiSwati was influenced by the fact that King Madzikane\u2019s mother was from one of the Royal Houses of the Swatis of aMalambo. He grew up within the Swatis from his mother\u2019s side and therefore spoke the language. Although he accepts that he is not an authority on this, Jordan, A.C. (1953) argues and also asserts that in the traditional history of the Bhacas, \u201cuDlamini and kwaDlamini\u201d figure a great deal (P.5). He further states that the Bhaca language was stifled to death chiefly by isiXhasa through, amongst others, schools and churches and that a large number of enlightened Bhacas were taught to look down upon their mother tongue.\n\nDiko is the first son of Ncapayi, (Makhohlisa a daughter of Dzanibe clan was the first wife of Ncapayi) with his younger brother Sogoni from the first wife of Ncaphayi. The younger brother from the second wife was Inkosi Makaula followed by Inkosi Dabula and others from other younger wives. Inkosi Madzikane ll Diko is the crown prince of iNkosi Dilizintaba, ka Dingumhlaba, ka Mabhijela i, ka  kaMthakathi, kaQoza ka Diko ka Ncaphayi, ka Madzikane, ka Khalimeshe, ka Vebi, ka Wabane, ka Didi, ka Zulu, ka Ntombela, ka Malandela, ka Dlungwana, ka Ndaba.\n\nINkosi Madzikane II Thandisizwe Diko is currently the head of the kwaBhaca/LuBhacweni Traditional Council at ELundzini Royal Kraal, Ncunteni Great Place, LuBhacweni A/A in Mount Frere, KwaBhaca.\n\nAmaBhaca were therefore stripped off their dignity and their Kingdomship by the colonial powers, the Boers, the [[Griqua people|Griquas]] and later on, the [[apartheid]]  did not make it any better. The home of the Bhacas is in Mount Frere, while other Bhacas who went back to KwaZulu are in Mzimkhulu and Ixopo under the Zulu Kingdom.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Bhaca kings]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bhaca.co.za Bhaca| AmaBhaca]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:19th-century monarchs in Africa]]\n[[Category:South African chiefs]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of South Africa]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "FeanorStar7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madzikane"}
{"title_page": "Dammit Janet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{For|the ''Family Guy'' episode|Dammit Janet (Family Guy)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Dammit Janet\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = Richard O'Brien. Performed by Barry Bostwick, Susan Sarandon\n| album    = The Rocky Horror Picture Show: Music From The Motion Picture\n| released = 1975\n| format   =\n| recorded = London\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    =\n| length   =\n| label    = [[Ode Records]]\n| writer   = Composer: Richard O'Brien, [[Richard Hartley (composer)|Richard Hartley]]<br>Lyricist: Richard O'Brien\n| producer = [[Lou Adler]]\n| tracks   =\n# \"[[Science Fiction/Double Feature]]\"\n# \"'''Dammit Janet'''\"\n# \"[[Over at the Frankenstein Place]]\"\n# \"[[Time Warp (song)|Time Warp]]\"\n# \"[[Sweet Transvestite]]\"\n# \"[[I Can Make You a Man]]\"\n# \"[[Hot Patootie - Bless My Soul]]\"\n# \"[[I Can Make You a Man|I Can Make You a Man (Reprise)]]\"\n# \"[[Touch-a, Touch-a, Touch-a, Touch Me]]\"\n# \"[[Eddie (Rocky Horror song)|Eddie]]\"\n# \"Floor Show\"\n## \"[[Rose Tint My World]]\n## \"[[Fanfare/Don't Dream It, Be It|Fanfare/Don't Dream It]]\"\n## \"[[Wild and Untamed Thing]]\"\n# \"[[I'm Going Home (Rocky Horror song)|I'm Going Home]]\"\n# \"Super Heroes\"\n# \"[[Science Fiction/Double Feature|Science Fiction/Double Feature (Reprise)]]\"\n}}\n\n\"'''Dammit Janet'''\" is a song/musical number in the original 1973 British musical [[stage play|stage]] production, ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' as well as its 1975 [[film]] counterpart ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', book, music and lyrics by [[Richard O'Brien]], musical arrangements by [[Richard Hartley (composer)|Richard Hartley]].\n\nThe number provides well known audience participation moments and has entered the popular culture lexicon through the often quoted phrase ''\"Dammit, Janet!\"''\n\n==Overview==\nThe first scene of both the stage production and film open to a wedding scene with the two main characters, Brad Majors and Janet Weiss, in attendance. In the motion picture, a repressive Gothic setting, backs up the young couple in their chorus with the ''[[American Gothic]]'' characters themselves.<ref>{{cite book| title=American Gothic| last=Biel, Wood| first=Steven, Grant| publisher=W. W. Norton & Company; illustrated edition| year=2005| pages=[https://archive.org/details/americangothicli00biel/page/54 54]| isbn=978-0-393-05912-0| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/americangothicli00biel/page/54}}</ref> Brad and Janet are portrayed as sexually uptight.<ref>{{cite book |title = Listening to the sirens | last=Peraino| first=Judith Ann | publisher = University of California Press|year = 2005| pages = 233 | isbn=978-0-520-21587-0 }}</ref> The song is performed in this deliberate awkwardness, setting up the characters as naive and innocent. \n\nThe scene is reminiscent of the opening scene of the horror classic ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' (1968). Several comparisons ''Rocky Horror'' with ''Night of the Living Dead'' have been made by authors such as Roberta E. Pearson and Philip Simpson in their book, ''Critical Dictionary of Film and Television Theory'',<ref>{{cite book |title = Critical dictionary of film and television theory | last= Pearson, Simpson| first=Roberta, Philip| publisher = Routledge|year = 2000| pages = 152| isbn=978-0-415-16218-0 }}</ref> as well as [[J. Hoberman]] and [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] in the book, ''Midnight Movies''.<ref>{{cite book |title = Midnight movies | last=Hoberman,  Rosenbaum| first=J., Jonathan| publisher = Da Capo Press |year = 1991| pages = 1| isbn=978-0-306-80433-5 }}</ref> Costumes for the two characters in this scene are nearly identical to those of the two main characters from the film ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'' (1972).\n\nThe song is an awkward musical marriage proposal by Brad to Janet, after both have attended the wedding of two high school friends, just before setting off to visit their high school science teacher.<ref>{{cite book |title = Theatre and Holy Script | last=Levy| first=Shimon| publisher = Sussex Academic Press |year = 1998 | pages = 174 | isbn=978-1-898723-53-0 }}</ref> The music for the song exaggerates the Rock-N-Roll tendency to repeat simple chord progressions.<ref>{{cite book |title = The American musical and the performance of personal identity | last=Knapp | first=Raymond| publisher =Princeton University Press |year = 2006| pages = 246| isbn=978-0-691-12524-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe song is in the key of [[B-flat major|B\u266d major]].\n\n== Musical Number ==\n\"Dammit Janet\" is the second number in the stage production following the prologue, and is performed as a duet. Act One, Scene 1 opens directly on Brad and Janet as they are waving goodbye to newly wedded friends Ralph and Betty Hapschatt. For the film, the exterior location was an American-style small-town church. The original film script refers to it as the Denton Catholic Church, but as seen in the final film, it is the Denton Episcopal Church.\n\nA notable aspect of the film production for this number is the cemetery next to the church with a billboard in the distance for comical effect. It depicts a large heart with an arrow through it with the words, \"Denton, the Home of Happiness\". Brad and Janet stand on opposite sides of the screen with the cemetery in the background and the billboard far in the back, but directly between each character as the song begins.\n\nBeginning in an awkward and uncertain proclamation by Brad that he \"Has Something to say\". Janet awaits, clutching the bridal bouquet she just caught. In musical rhythm, he tells Janet that he really loves \"The Skillful Way\" she beat the other girls to the bride's bouquet.\n\nHe professes his love with metaphors of deep rivers and the future, all accompanied by the church staff dressed exactly as characters from the classic painting ''[[American Gothic]]'' by [[Grant Wood]]. The back-up throughout the stage play was a cast of \"Chorus\" singers credited as \"Phantoms\".\n\nThe scene in the movie begins to change. As the number progresses, we follow the couple into the church while the caretaker and staff begin to prepare for a funeral. They spin the white flower arrangements around to show that they are black on the other side, and a casket is carried in and placed in front of them just as Brad and Janet kiss.\n\n==Reception==\nThe song is considered to be one of the top \"heartfelt\" movie moments.<ref name=\"valentine\">{{cite news |last=Berg |first=Ken |date=8 February 1991 |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |title=Valentine videos; Simmering cinema at home |page=16}}</ref> Further, the words \"Damn it, Janet\" are seen as an immortal part of cinematic history.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Albuquerque Tribune]] |date=28 October 1995 |title=TV Queen |page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Silver |first=Vernon |date=20 November 1994 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Film; A New Breed of Cult Favorites for a New Generation |page=224}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the characters of ''The Rocky Horror Picture Show'', the phrase \"Dammit, Janet!\" has entered the pop culture lexicon.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scheck |first=Frank |date=16 November 2000 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |title=The Rocky Horror Show |volume=Volume 365 |issue=Issue 36 |page=10}}</ref> The phrase has become so ingrained in society that thirty years after first singing the song for the film, American actor [[Barry Bostwick]] told an interviewer \"For as long as I live, people will be coming up to me and asking me to say, \"Dammit, Janet. I love you.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bonko |first=Larry |date=4 July 2003 |newspaper=[[The Virginian-Pilot|Virginia Pilot and Ledger-Star]] |title=Celebrate Independence Day without leaving home |page=E1}}</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\nIn 1996, the Scottish-rooted band Choke released an [[Extended play|extended play record]] entitled ''Damn It Janet''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=Jamie J. |date=5 January 2001 |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |title=Scottish-rooted Choke has come a long way |page=15}}</ref> Four years later, Australian musical artists Pants & Corset released an [[Red Book (audio CD standard)|Audio CD]] entitled ''Dammit Janet''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Padilla |first=David |date=12 May 2000 |newspaper=[[The Miami Herald]] |title=Untitled |page=20S}}</ref> Also in 2000, [[20th Century Fox]] licensed a greeting card featuring the signature lip logo of ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' on the cover and a picture in the inside of Brad holding Janet and saying ''Dammit, Janet! Pull yourself together. It's only a [[birthday card]]! Happy Birthday, you... you monster!''<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Mike |date=6 October 2000 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |title=Let's do the Time Warp -- on DVD. |page=3E}}</ref> \"[[Dammit Janet!]]\" was also the name of an episode of ''[[Family Guy]]''; in which Stewie falls in love with a girl in his preschool class named Janet. \"Dammit Janet\" was also sung on the television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. In the 2019 Hulu original series ''[[Reprisal (TV series)|Reprisal]]'', \"Dammit Janet\" is playing on the record player while Katherine and her former husband Bash lip-sync to the song.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/dammit-janet/11040480]\n\n{{The Rocky Horror Picture Show}}\n\n[[Category:1973 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rocky Horror]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Hartley]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Richard O'Brien]]\n[[Category:Male\u2013female vocal duets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{For|the ''Family Guy'' episode|Dammit Janet (Family Guy)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Dammit Janet\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = Richard O'Brien. Performed by Barry Bostwick, Susan Sarandon\n| album    = The Rocky Horror Picture Show: Music From The Motion Picture\n| released = 1975\n| format   =\n| recorded = London\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    =\n| length   =\n| label    = [[Ode Records]]\n| writer   = Composer: Richard O'Brien, [[Richard Hartley (composer)|Richard Hartley]]<br>Lyricist: Richard O'Brien\n| producer = [[Lou Adler]]\n| tracks   =\n# \"[[Science Fiction/Double Feature]]\"\n# \"'''Dammit Janet'''\"\n# \"[[Over at the Frankenstein Place]]\"\n# \"[[Time Warp (song)|Time Warp]]\"\n# \"[[Sweet Transvestite]]\"\n# \"[[I Can Make You a Man]]\"\n# \"[[Hot Patootie - Bless My Soul]]\"\n# \"[[I Can Make You a Man|I Can Make You a Man (Reprise)]]\"\n# \"[[Touch-a, Touch-a, Touch-a, Touch Me]]\"\n# \"[[Eddie (Rocky Horror song)|Eddie]]\"\n# \"Floor Show\"\n## \"[[Rose Tint My World]]\n## \"[[Fanfare/Don't Dream It, Be It|Fanfare/Don't Dream It]]\"\n## \"[[Wild and Untamed Thing]]\"\n# \"[[I'm Going Home (Rocky Horror song)|I'm Going Home]]\"\n# \"Super Heroes\"\n# \"[[Science Fiction/Double Feature|Science Fiction/Double Feature (Reprise)]]\"\n}}\n\n\"'''Dammit Janet'''\" is a song/musical number in the original 1973 British musical [[stage play|stage]] production, ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' as well as its 1975 [[film]] counterpart ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', book, music and lyrics by [[Richard O'Brien]], musical arrangements by [[Richard Hartley (composer)|Richard Hartley]].\n\nThe number provides well known audience participation moments and has entered the popular culture lexicon through the often quoted phrase ''\"Dammit, Janet!\"''\n\n==Overview==\nThe first scene of both the stage production and film open to a wedding scene with the two main characters, Brad Majors and Janet Weiss, in attendance. In the motion picture, a repressive Gothic setting, backs up the young couple in their chorus with the \"[[American Gothic]]\" characters themselves.<ref>{{cite book| title=American Gothic| last=Biel, Wood| first=Steven, Grant| publisher=W. W. Norton & Company; illustrated edition| year=2005| pages=[https://archive.org/details/americangothicli00biel/page/54 54]| isbn=978-0-393-05912-0| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/americangothicli00biel/page/54}}</ref> Brad and Janet are portrayed as sexually uptight.<ref>{{cite book |title = Listening to the sirens | last=Peraino| first=Judith Ann | publisher = University of California Press|year = 2005| pages = 233 | isbn=978-0-520-21587-0 }}</ref> The song is performed in this deliberate awkwardness, setting up the characters as naive and innocent. \n\nThe scene is reminiscent of the opening scene of the horror classic ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' (1968). Several comparisons ''Rocky Horror'' with ''Night of the Living Dead'' have been made by authors such as Roberta E. Pearson and Philip Simpson in their book, ''Critical Dictionary of Film and Television Theory'',<ref>{{cite book |title = Critical dictionary of film and television theory | last= Pearson, Simpson| first=Roberta, Philip| publisher = Routledge|year = 2000| pages = 152| isbn=978-0-415-16218-0 }}</ref> as well as [[J. Hoberman]] and [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] in the book, ''Midnight Movies''.<ref>{{cite book |title = Midnight movies | last=Hoberman,  Rosenbaum| first=J., Jonathan| publisher = Da Capo Press |year = 1991| pages = 1| isbn=978-0-306-80433-5 }}</ref> Costumes for the two characters in this scene are nearly identical to those of the two main characters from the film ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'' (1972).\n\nThe song is an awkward musical marriage proposal by Brad to Janet, after both have attended the wedding of two high school friends, just before setting off to visit their high school science teacher.<ref>{{cite book |title = Theatre and Holy Script | last=Levy| first=Shimon| publisher = Sussex Academic Press |year = 1998 | pages = 174 | isbn=978-1-898723-53-0 }}</ref> The music for the song exaggerates the Rock-N-Roll tendency to repeat simple chord progressions.<ref>{{cite book |title = The American musical and the performance of personal identity | last=Knapp | first=Raymond| publisher =Princeton University Press |year = 2006| pages = 246| isbn=978-0-691-12524-4 }}</ref>\n\nThe song is in the key of [[B-flat major|B\u266d major]].\n\n== Musical Number ==\n\"Dammit Janet\" is the second number in the stage production following the prologue, and is performed as a duet. Act One, Scene 1 opens directly on Brad and Janet as they are waving goodbye to newly wedded friends Ralph and Betty Hapschatt. For the film, the exterior location was an American-style small-town church. The original film script refers to it as the Denton Catholic Church, but as seen in the final film, it is the Denton Episcopal Church.\n\nA notable aspect of the film production for this number is the cemetery next to the church with a billboard in the distance for comical effect. It depicts a large heart with an arrow through it with the words, \"Denton, the Home of Happiness\". Brad and Janet stand on opposite sides of the screen with the cemetery in the background and the billboard far in the back, but directly between each character as the song begins.\n\nBeginning in an awkward and uncertain proclamation by Brad that he \"Has Something to say\". Janet awaits, clutching the bridal bouquet she just caught. In musical rhythm, he tells Janet that he really loves \"The Skillful Way\" she beat the other girls to the bride's bouquet.\n\nHe professes his love with metaphors of deep rivers and the future, all accompanied by the church staff dressed exactly as characters from the classic painting ''[[American Gothic]]'' by [[Grant Wood]]. The back-up throughout the stage play was a cast of \"Chorus\" singers credited as \"Phantoms\".\n\nThe scene in the movie begins to change. As the number progresses, we follow the couple into the church while the caretaker and staff begin to prepare for a funeral. They spin the white flower arrangements around to show that they are black on the other side, and a casket is carried in and placed in front of them just as Brad and Janet kiss.\n\n==Reception==\nThe song is considered to be one of the top \"heartfelt\" movie moments.<ref name=\"valentine\">{{cite news |last=Berg |first=Ken |date=8 February 1991 |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |title=Valentine videos; Simmering cinema at home |page=16}}</ref> Further, the words \"Damn it, Janet\" are seen as an immortal part of cinematic history.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Albuquerque Tribune]] |date=28 October 1995 |title=TV Queen |page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Silver |first=Vernon |date=20 November 1994 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Film; A New Breed of Cult Favorites for a New Generation |page=224}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the characters of ''The Rocky Horror Picture Show'', the phrase \"Dammit, Janet!\" has entered the pop culture lexicon.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scheck |first=Frank |date=16 November 2000 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |title=The Rocky Horror Show |volume=Volume 365 |issue=Issue 36 |page=10}}</ref> The phrase has become so ingrained in society that thirty years after first singing the song for the film, American actor [[Barry Bostwick]] told an interviewer \"For as long as I live, people will be coming up to me and asking me to say, \"Dammit, Janet. I love you.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bonko |first=Larry |date=4 July 2003 |newspaper=[[The Virginian-Pilot|Virginia Pilot and Ledger-Star]] |title=Celebrate Independence Day without leaving home |page=E1}}</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\nIn 1996, the Scottish-rooted band Choke released an [[Extended play|extended play record]] entitled ''Damn It Janet''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=Jamie J. |date=5 January 2001 |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |title=Scottish-rooted Choke has come a long way |page=15}}</ref> Four years later, Australian musical artists Pants & Corset released an [[Red Book (audio CD standard)|Audio CD]] entitled ''Dammit Janet''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Padilla |first=David |date=12 May 2000 |newspaper=[[The Miami Herald]] |title=Untitled |page=20S}}</ref> Also in 2000, [[20th Century Fox]] licensed a greeting card featuring the signature lip logo of ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' on the cover and a picture in the inside of Brad holding Janet and saying ''Dammit, Janet! Pull yourself together. It's only a [[birthday card]]! Happy Birthday, you... you monster!''<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Mike |date=6 October 2000 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |title=Let's do the Time Warp -- on DVD. |page=3E}}</ref> \"[[Dammit Janet!]]\" was also the name of an episode of ''[[Family Guy]]''; in which Stewie falls in love with a girl in his preschool class named Janet. \"Dammit Janet\" was also sung on the television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. In the 2019 Hulu original series ''[[Reprisal (TV series)|Reprisal]]'', \"Dammit Janet\" is playing on the record player while Katherine and her former husband Bash lip-sync to the song.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/dammit-janet/11040480]\n\n{{The Rocky Horror Picture Show}}\n\n[[Category:1973 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rocky Horror]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Hartley]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Richard O'Brien]]\n[[Category:Male\u2013female vocal duets]]\n", "name_user": "Packer1028", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dammit_Janet"}
{"title_page": "DevOps", "text_new": "{{short description|Set of software development practices}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=December 2018}}\n{{Software development process}}\n'''DevOps''' is a set of practices that combines [[software development]] (''Dev'') and [[information technology operations|information-technology operations]] (''Ops'') which aims to shorten the [[systems development life cycle]] and provide [[continuous delivery]] with high [[software quality]].<ref name=\"Mala 2019 p. 16\">{{cite book | last=Mala | first=D.J. | title=Integrating the Internet of Things Into Software Engineering Practices | publisher=IGI Global | series=Advances in Systems Analysis, Software Engineering, and High Performance Computing | year=2019 | isbn=978-1-5225-7791-1 | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GPGCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 | access-date=4 April 2019 | page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"loukides-2012\">{{Cite web|url=http://radar.oreilly.com/2012/06/what-is-devops.html|title=What is DevOps?|last=Loukides|first=Mike|date=7 June 2012|publisher=[[O'Reilly_Media]]}}</ref> \n\n==Definition==\nAcademics and practitioners have not developed a unique definition for the term \"DevOps.\"{{efn|Dyck et. al (2015) \"To our knowledge, there is no uniform definition for the terms release engineering and DevOps. As a consequence, many people use their own definitions or rely on others, which results in confusion about those terms.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1= Andrej |last1= Dyck |first2= Ralf |last2= Penners |first3= Horst |last3= Lichter |title= Towards Definitions for Release Engineering and DevOps |journal=Proceedings of the 2015 IEEE/ACM 3rd International Workshop on Release Engineering |date=2015-05-19 |publisher=[[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] }}</ref>}}{{efn|Jabbari et. al (2016) \"The research results of this study showed the need for a definition as individual studies do not consistently define DevOps.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Ramtin |last1=Jabbari |first2=Nauman |last2=bin Ali |first3=Kai |last3=Petersen |first4=Binish |last4=Tanveer |journal=Proceedings of the 2016 Scientific Workshop |date=May 2016 |publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery]] |title=What is DevOps?: A Systematic Mapping Study on Definitions and Practices }}</ref>}}{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We noticed that there are various gaps in the study of DevOps: There is no consensus of what concepts DevOps covers, nor how DevOps is defined.\"<ref name=\"erich-2017\">{{cite journal |title=A Qualitative Study of DevOps Usage in Practice |first1=F.M.A. |last1=Erich |first2=C. |last2=Amrit |first3=M. |last3=Daneva |journal=Journal of Software: Evolution and Process |volume=29 |issue=6 |date=June 2017 }}</ref>}}{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We discovered that there exists little agreement about the characteristics of DevOps in the academic literature.\"<ref name=\"erich-2017\"/>}}\n\nFrom an academic perspective, [[Len Bass]], [[Ingo Weber]], and [[Liming Zhu]] \u2014 three computer science researchers from the [[CSIRO]] and the [[Software Engineering Institute]] \u2014 suggested defining DevOps as \"a set of practices intended to reduce the time between committing a change to a system and the change being placed into normal production, while ensuring high quality\".<ref>{{cite book|title=DevOps: A Software Architect's Perspective|author1=Bass, Len|author2=Weber, Ingo|author3=Zhu, Liming|isbn=978-0134049847|year=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe term DevOps, however, has been used in multiple contexts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://devops.com/surprise-broad-agreement-on-the-definition-of-devops/|title=Surprise! Broad Agreement on the Definition of DevOps|date=2015-05-13|website=DevOps.com|}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=February 2019}}\n\n==History==\n{{undue|section|date=December 2018}}\nIn 2009, the first conference named devopsdays was held in [[Ghent]], [[Belgium]]. The conference was founded by Belgian consultant, project manager and agile practitioner Patrick Debois.<ref name=\"devops-name\">{{cite web|last=Mezak|first=Steve|title=The Origins of DevOps: What's in a Name?|url=https://devops.com/the-origins-of-devops-whats-in-a-name/|publisher = devops.com|accessdate=6 May 2019|date=25 January 2018}}</ref>{{who|date=December 2018}}<ref name=\"jediblog\">{{cite web|last=Debois|first=Patrick|title=Agile 2008 Toronto|url=http://www.jedi.be/blog/2008/10/09/agile-2008-toronto-agile-infrastructure-and-operations-presentation/|publisher=Just Enough Documented Information|accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> The conference has now spread to other countries.<ref name=\"devopsdays\">{{cite web|last=Debois|first=Patrick|title=DevOps Days|url=http://www.devopsdays.org/|publisher = DevOps Days|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the State of DevOps report was conceived and launched by Alanna Brown at Puppet.<ref name=\"2016 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2016.pdf|title=2016 State of DevOps Report|author1=Alana Brown|author2=Nicole Forsgren|date=2016|publisher=Puppet Labs, DORA (DevOps Research|access-date=2019-05-06|author3=Jez Humble|author4=Nigel Kersten|author5=Gene Kim}}</ref><ref name=\"Alanna Brown\">{{cite web|title=Puppet - Alanna Brown|url=https://puppet.com/blog/author/alanna-brown|publisher=Puppet Labs|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> \nAs of 2014, the annual State of DevOps report was published by Nicole Forsgren, Gene Kim, Jez Humble and others.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|author1=Nicole Forsgren|author2=Gene Kim|author3=Nigel Kersten |author4=Jez Humble|title=2014 State of DevOps Report|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2014.pdf|date=2014|publisher=Puppet Labs, IT Revolution Press and ThoughtWorks |access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|title=2015 State of DevOps Report|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2015.pdf|date=2015|publisher=Puppet Labs, Pwc, IT Revolution Press|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\nIn 2014, they found that DevOps adoption was accelerating.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\nAlso in 2014, Lisa Crispin and Janet Gregory wrote the book More Agile Testing, containing a chapter on testing and DevOps.<ref name=\"More Agile Testing - TOC\">{{cite web|title=More Agile Testing|url=https://agiletester.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/26/2014/09/TOC.pdf|date=October 2014|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref><ref name=\"More Agile Testing\">{{cite book|title=More Agile Testing|url=https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/more-agile-testing/9780133749571/|last=Crispin|first=Lisa|last2=Gregory|first2=Janet|date=October 2014|isbn=9780133749571 |access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Toolchains==\n{{unreliable sources|section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Main|DevOps toolchain}}\nAs DevOps is intended to be a cross-functional mode of working, those that practice the methodology use different sets of tools&mdash;referred to as \"[[DevOps toolchain|toolchains]]\"&mdash;rather than a single one.<ref>{{cite report |title=Gartner Market Trends: DevOps \u2013 Not a Market, but Tool-Centric Philosophy That supports a Continuous Delivery Value Chain |publisher=Gartner |date=18 February 2015}}</ref> These toolchains are expected to fit into one or more of the following categories, reflective of key aspects of the development and delivery process:<ref>{{cite web| title=Integrating DevOps tools into a Service Delivery Platform|last=Edwards|first=Damon|url=http://dev2ops.org/2012/07/integrating-devops-tools-into-a-service-delivery-platform-video/|website=dev2ops.org}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Exploring the ENTIRE DevOps Toolchain for (Cloud) Teams|last=Seroter|first=Richard|url= http://www.infoq.com/articles/devops-toolchain|website=infoq.com}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}\n#Coding \u2013 code development and review, [[Version control|source code management]] tools, code merging \n#Building \u2013 [[continuous integration]] tools, build status\n#Testing \u2013 [[continuous testing]] tools that provide quick and timely feedback on business risks\n#Packaging \u2013 [[Binary repository manager|artifact repository]], application pre-deployment staging\n#Releasing \u2013 change management, release approvals, [[application release automation|release automation]] \n#Configuring \u2013 infrastructure configuration and management, [[infrastructure as code]] tools\n#Monitoring \u2013 [[Application performance management|applications performance monitoring]], end-user experience\n\nSome categories are more essential in a DevOps toolchain than others; especially continuous integration (e.g. [[Jenkins (software)|Jenkins]], [[Gitlab]], [[Bitbucket]] pipelines) and infrastructure as code (e.g., [[Terraform (software)|Terraform]], [[Ansible (software)|Ansible]], [[Puppet (software)|Puppet]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://devops.com/2016/02/05/devops-stack-shoestring-budget/|title=DevOps Stack on a Shoestring Budget|last=Theakanath|first=Thomas|website=devops.com|date=2016-02-05}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}<ref>{{Cite web|title = Stronger DevOps Culture with Puppet and Vagrant|url = https://puppetlabs.com/blog/stronger-devops-culture-with-puppet-and-vagrant|website = Puppet Labs|accessdate = 22 October 2015}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}\n\nForsgren ''et al.'' found that IT performance is strongly correlated with DevOps practices like [[Version control|source code management]] and [[continuous delivery]].<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\n==Relationship to other approaches==\n=== Agile ===\n{{Main|Agile software development}}\nAgile and DevOps serve complementary roles: several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, [[continuous integration]], and [[continuous delivery]] originated in the Agile world, which dates (informally) to the 1990s, and formally to 2001.<ref name=WattsKidd>{{cite web |url=https://www.bmc.com/blogs/devops-vs-agile-whats-the-difference-and-how-are-they-related/ |title=DevOps vs Agile: What's the Difference and How Are They Related? |first1=Stephen |last1=Watts |first2=Chrissy |last2=Kidd |website=bmc.com |date=August 10, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Agile can be viewed as addressing communication gaps between customers and developers, while DevOps addresses gaps between developers and IT operations / infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guru99.com/agile-vs-devops.html |title=Agile Vs. DevOps: What's the difference? |website=guru99.com |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Also, DevOps has focus on the deployment of developed software, whether it is developed via Agile or other methodologies.<ref name=WattsKidd/>.\n\n===ArchOps===\nArchOps presents an extension for DevOps practice, starting from [[software architecture]] artifacts, instead of source code, for operation deployment.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Castellanos |first1=Camilo |last2=Correal |first2=Dario |date=15 September 2018|title=Executing Architectural Models for Big Data Analytics |journal=Lecture Notes in Computer Science |volume=11048 |issue= |pages=364\u2013371 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-00761-4_24 |isbn=978-3-030-00760-7 }}</ref>. ArchOps states that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.\n\n===TestOps===\nTestOps is to hardware development what DevOps is to software development. The idea is a toolchain that links design and ''test'' ''op''eration''s'' together. In the case of hardware, design means [[Electronic design automation|EDA]] tools and the [[CAD]] department, and test means electronic measurement equipment like oscilloscopes and so on.<ref name=\"pathwave\">{{Cite web\n| title = The TestOps Manifesto: A Blueprint for Connected, Agile Design and Test\n| author = Keysight\n| date = 2019-03-19\n| access-date = 2019-09-11\n| url = http://literature.cdn.keysight.com/litweb/pdf/5992-3771EN.pdf\n| language =  \n| quote = Companies that embrace DevOps workflows report 29% greater productivity from their engineers. TestOps \u2013 DevOps for design and test \u2013 promises similar benefits. \n}}</ref>\n\n=== Continuous delivery ===\n{{Main|Continuous delivery}}\nContinuous delivery and DevOps have common goals and are often used in conjunction, but there are subtle differences.<ref name=\"CD_HJ\">{{cite book|title=Continuous Delivery: reliable software releases through build, test, and deployment automation|last=Humble|first=Jez|last2=Farley|first2=David|date=2011|publisher=Pearson Education Inc.|isbn=978-0-321-60191-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hammond|first=Jeffrey|date=9 September 2011|title=The Relationship between DevOps and Continuous Delivery|url=http://blogs.forrester.com/jeffrey_hammond/11-09-09-the_relationship_between_dev_ops_and_continuous_delivery_a_conversation_with_jez_humble_of_thought|journal=Forrester Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> \n\nWhile continuous delivery is focused on automating the processes in [[software delivery]], DevOps also focuses on the organizational change to support great collaboration between the many functions involved.<ref name=\"CD_HJ\" />\n\nDevOps and continuous delivery share a common background in [[Agile software development|agile methods]] and [[lean thinking]]: small and frequent changes with focused value to the end customer.<ref name=\"Agile Now\">{{cite journal|last=Ambler|first=Scott W.|date=12 February 2014|title=We need more Agile IT Now!|url=http://www.drdobbs.com/architecture-and-design/we-need-more-agile-it-now/240169361?queryText=Release%2Bmanagement|journal=Dr. Dobb's the World of Software Development}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} \n[[Lean manufacturing|Lean management]] and continuous delivery are fundamental to delivering value faster, in a sustainable way.<ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\nContinuous delivery focuses on making sure the software is always in a releasable state throughout its lifecycle.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/> This makes it cheaper and less risky to deliver the software.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\nImproved collaboration and communication both between and within organizational teams can help achieve faster [[time to market]], with reduced risks.<ref name=\"CD_LC\">{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1109/MS.2015.27|title = Continuous Delivery: Huge Benefits, but Challenges Too|journal = IEEE Software|volume = 32|issue = 2|pages = 50\u201354|year = 2015|last1 = Chen|first1 = Lianping}}</ref><ref name=\"Micro_Chen\">{{cite conference \n|url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323944215\n|title= Microservices: Architecting for Continuous Delivery and DevOps\n|first= Lianping |last= Chen \n|date= 2018 \n|conference= The IEEE International Conference on Software Architecture (ICSA 2018)\n|conferenceurl= http://icsa-conferences.org/2018/ \n|publisher= IEEE\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===DataOps===\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\n{{Main|DataOps}}\nThe application of continuous delivery and DevOps to data analytics has been termed DataOps. DataOps seeks to integrate data engineering, data integration, data quality, data security, and data privacy with operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tamr.com/from-devops-to-dataops-by-andy-palmer/|title=From DevOps to DataOps, By Andy Palmer - Tamr Inc.|date=7 May 2015|work=Tamr Inc.|access-date=23 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} It applies principles from DevOps, [[Agile software development|Agile Development]] and the [[statistical process control]], used in [[lean manufacturing]], to improve the cycle time of extracting value from data analytics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/data-ops/how-to-become-a-rising-star-with-data-analytics-6e4f611e85dd|title=How to Become a Rising Star with Data Analytics|last=DataKitchen|date=15 March 2017|website=data-ops|access-date=23 August 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Site-reliability engineering ===\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\n{{Main|Site reliability engineering}}\nIn 2003, [[Google]] developed [[site reliability engineering]] (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale high-availability systems while maintaining high-quality end-user experience.<ref>{{cite book|title=Site Reliability Engineering|date=April 2016|publisher=O'Reilly Media|first1=Betsy|last1=Beyer|first2=Chris|last2=Jones|first3=Jennifer|last3=Petoff|first4=Niall Richard|last4=Murphy|isbn=978-1-4919-2909-4}}</ref> While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://devops.com/sre-vs-devops-false-distinction/|title=SRE vs. DevOps \u2014 a False Distinction? - DevOps.com|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Systems administration===\n{{expand section|date=June 2018}}\nDevOps is often viewed as an approach to applying [[systems administrator|systems administration]] work to cloud technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techbeacon.com/sysadmins-survival-guide-devops|title=How to stay relevant in the DevOps era: A SysAdmin's survival guide}}</ref>\n\n===WinOps===\n{{main|WinOps}}\n[[WinOps]] is the term used for DevOps practices for a Microsoft-centric view.{{Citation needed|reason=WinOps is the proper noun of a conference.|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Toyota production system, lean thinking, kaizen===\n{{main|Toyota Production System}}\nToyota production system, TPS, implemented [[continuous improvement process|continuous improvement]], [[kaizen]], and [[lean thinking]] early. The [[Andon (manufacturing)|Andon cord principle]] to create fast feedback, swarm and solve problems stems from TPS. <ref>[https://opensource.com/article/18/11/analyzing-devops Analyzing the DNA of DevOps], Brent Aaron Reed, Willy Schaub, 2018-11-14.</ref><ref>The DevOps Handbook: How to Create World-Class Agility, Reliability, and Security in Technology Organizations, Gene Kim, Patrick Debois, John Willis, Jezz Humble, 2016</ref>\n\n===DevSecOps, Shifting Security Left===\n\nDevSecOps is an augmentation of DevOps to allow for security practices to be integrated into the DevOps approach. The traditional centralised security team model must adopt a federated model allowing each delivery team the ability to factor in the correct security controls into their DevOps practices.\n\n==Goals==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nIT performance can be measured in terms of throughput and stability. <ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\" />\nThroughput can be measured by deployment frequency and lead time for changes; stability can be measured by mean time to recover. The State of DevOps Reports found that investing in practices that increase these throughput and stability measures increase IT performance.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/><ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\nThe goals of DevOps span the entire delivery pipeline. They include:{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n* Improved deployment frequency;  \n* Faster [[time to market]]; \n* Lower failure rate of new releases; \n* Shortened lead time between fixes;\n* Faster mean time to recovery (in the event of a new release crashing or otherwise disabling the current system). \nSimple processes become increasingly programmable and dynamic, using a DevOps approach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newrelic.com/devops/what-is-devops |title=What is DevOps? |publisher=NewRelic.com |accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} DevOps aims to maximize the predictability, efficiency, security, and maintainability of operational processes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cloudomelette.com/what-is-devops/|title=What is DevOps? {{!}} A Quick Guide|last=Sep 10|last2=Devops {{!}} 0|first2=2019 {{!}}|date=2019-09-10|website=CloudOmelette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Very often, automation supports this objective.\n\nDevOps integration targets [[Software delivery|product delivery]], [[continuous testing]], [[Software testing#Software quality assurance .28SQA.29|quality testing]], feature development, and [[maintenance release]]s in order to improve reliability and security and provide faster [[Development cycle|development]] and [[Software deployment|deployment]] cycles.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Many of the ideas (and people) involved in DevOps came from the [[enterprise systems management]] and [[agile software development]] movements.<ref name=\"AgileInf2010\">{{cite web|last=Nasrat|first=Paul|title=Agile Infrastructure|url=http://www.infoq.com/presentations/agile-infrastructure|publisher=InfoQ|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nPractices that correlate with deployment frequency are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Continuous delivery\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n\nPractices that correlate with a lead time for change are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n* Automated testing\n\nPractices that correlate with a mean time to recovery for change are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n* Monitoring system and application health \n\nCompanies {{failed verification span|that practice DevOps|date=February 2019}} have reported significant benefits, including: significantly shorter [[time to market]], improved customer satisfaction, better product quality, more reliable releases, improved productivity and efficiency, and the increased ability to build the right product by fast experimentation.<ref name=\"CD_LC\"/>\n\nThe 2014 State of DevOps Report found that \"IT performance strongly correlates with well-known DevOps practices such as the use of version\ncontrol and continuous delivery.\"<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\nThere is a lack of evidence in academic literature on the effectiveness of DevOps.{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We noticed that there are various gaps in the study of DevOps: [...] There is a lack of evidence on the effectiveness of DevOps.<ref name=\"erich-2017\" />}}\n\n==Cultural change==\nDevOps initiatives can create cultural changes in companies <ref>{{cite report |title=Emerging Technology Analysis: DevOps a Culture Shift, Not a Technology |publisher=Gartner}}</ref> by transforming the way [[Information technology operations|operations]], [[Software developer|developers]], and [[Software testing|testers]] collaborate during the development and delivery processes.<ref name=\"loukides-2012\" /> Getting these groups to work cohesively is a critical challenge in enterprise DevOps adoption.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gartner IT Glossary {{ndash}} devops|website=Gartner|url=http://www.gartner.com/it-glossary/devops/ | access-date= 30 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Jones et al\">{{Cite book| first1 = Stephen| title = Proceedings of the 2nd International Workshop on Quality-Aware Dev ''Ops'' - QUDOS 2016| pages = 7\u201311|last1 = Jones| first2 = Joost| last2 = Noppen|first3 = Fiona| last3 = Lettice| date = 21 July 2016| doi = 10.1145/2945408.2945410  | isbn = 9781450344111}}</ref> DevOps is as much about culture, as it is about the toolchain.<ref name=\"Building a DevOps culture\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oreilly.com/ideas/building-a-devops-culture|title=Building a DevOps culture|author= Mandi Walls|date=September 25, 2015|publisher=O'Reilly}}</ref> \n\n===DevOps as a job title===\n\nWhile DevOps describes an approach to work rather than a distinct role (like [[system administrator]]), job advertisements are increasingly using terms like \"''DevOps Engineer''\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://devops.com/is-devops-a-title/|title=Is DevOps a Title? - DevOps.com|date=20 March 2014|work=DevOps.com|access-date=22 July 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.monster.com/career-advice/article/devops-jobs|title=DevOps: A Job Title or a School of Thought?|work=Monster Career Advice|access-date=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile DevOps reflects complex topics, the DevOps community uses analogies to communicate important concepts,{{relevant inline|date=March 2019}} much like \"[[The Cathedral and the Bazaar]]\" from the open-source community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://devops.stackexchange.com/questions/1403/what-are-known-useful-and-misleading-memes-in-the-devops-culture|title=What are known useful and misleading memes in the DevOps culture?|website=devops.stackexchange.com|access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n* Cattle not Pets: the paradigm of disposable server infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/03/18/servers_pets_or_cattle_cern/|title=Are Your Servers Pets or Cattle?|last=Sharwood|first=Simon|website=[[The Register]]|access-date=2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* 10 deployments per day: the story of Flickr adopting DevOps.\n\n===Building a DevOps culture===\nOrganizational culture is a strong predictor of IT and organizational performance. Cultural practices such as information flow, collaboration, shared responsibilities, learning from failures and new ideas are central to DevOps.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/> Team-building and other [[employee engagement]] activities are often used to create an environment that fosters this communication and cultural change within an organization.<ref>{{cite book|last=Walls |first=Mandi | date= 15 April 2013 | title= Building a DevOps Culture| url= https://books.google.com/?id=XO1So8BTj2wC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | publisher=OReilly Media |isbn=9781449368364 }}</ref> Team\u2013building activities can include [[board game]]s, trust activities, and employee engagement seminars.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Roach |first=Patrick | title= Dice Breakers: Using DevOps principles and nerdery to reimagine Team building | url= http://devops.com/2015/10/08/dice-breakers-using-devops-principles-nerdery-reimagine-team-building/| journal=DevOps.com |date=2015-10-08 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe 2015 State of DevOps Report discovered that the top seven measures with the strongest correlation to organizational culture are:\n1. Organizational investment in DevOps:<ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n2. Team leaders' experience and effectiveness.\n3. Continuous delivery.\n4. The ability of different disciplines (development, operations, and infosec) to achieve\nwin-win outcomes.\n5. Organizational performance.\n6. Deployment pain.\n7. Lean management practices.\n\n==Deployment==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nCompanies with very frequent releases may require knowledge on DevOps.{{cn|date=March 2019}} For example, the company that operates image hosting website [[Flickr]] developed a DevOps approach to support ten deployments a day.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.slideshare.net/jallspaw/10-deploys-per-day-dev-and-ops-cooperation-at-flickr\n | title = 10+ Deploys Per Day: Dev and Ops Cooperation at Flickr\n| date = 2009-06-23\n}}</ref> Daily deployment cycle would be much higher at organizations producing multi-focus or multi-function applications.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Daily deployment is referred to as [[continuous deployment]]<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.svforum.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Calendar.eventDetail&eventID=13703\n | work = SVForum\n | title = SAM SIG: Applied Lean Startup Ideas: Continuous Deployment at kaChing\n | access-date = 20 June 2011\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121020133600/http://www.svforum.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Calendar.eventDetail&eventID=13703\n | archive-date = 20 October 2012\n | url-status = dead\n }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} or [[continuous delivery]] <ref>{{Cite web\n | url = https://www.cutter.com/article/why-enterprises-must-adopt-devops-enable-continuous-delivery-416516\n | title = Why Enterprises Must Adopt Devops to Enable Continuous Delivery \n | work = [[Cutter IT Journal]] | first = Jez | last = Humble \n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and has been associated with the [[lean startup]] methodology.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url =  http://www.slideshare.net/pascallouis/applied-lean-startup-ideas-continuous-deployment-at-kaching\n | title = Applied Lean Startup Ideas: Continuous Deployment at kaChing\n| date = 2010-05-26\n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} [[Professional association]]s and [[blog|blogs post]]s have formed on the topic since 2009.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.devopsdays.org/events/2009-ghent/\n | title = DevOps Days 2009 Conference\n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://dev2ops.org/blog/2010/4/26/devops-meetup-recap.html\n | title = DevOps Meetup Recap | first = Damon | last = Edwards\n}}\n</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Architecturally significant requirements===\nTo practice DevOps effectively, software applications have to meet a set of [[architecturally significant requirements]] (ASRs), such as: deployability, modifiability, testability, and monitorability.<ref name=\"ArchCD_LC\">{{cite conference |title=Towards Architecting for Continuous Delivery|first=Lianping |last=Chen|year=2015|place=Montr\u00e9al, Canada |conference=The 12th Working IEEE/IFIP Conference on Software Architecture(WICSA 2015)|conferenceurl=http://wicsa2015.org/ |publisher=IEEE|doi=10.1109/WICSA.2015.23}}</ref> These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.\n\n===Microservices===\nAlthough in principle it is possible to practice DevOps with any architectural style, the [[microservices]] architectural style is becoming the standard for building continuously deployed systems.<ref name=\"Micro_Chen\"/> Small size service allows the architecture of an individual service to emerge through continuous refactoring,<ref name=\"Ach_Chen\">{{cite conference |title=Towards an Evidence-Based Understanding of Emergence of Architecture through Continuous Refactoring in Agile Software Development|first=Lianping |last=Chen |first2=Muhammad|last2=Ali Babar|date=2014 |conference=The 11th Working IEEE/IFIP Conference on Software Architecture(WICSA 2014)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730053454/http://wicsa2014.org/ |publisher=IEEE|doi=10.1109/WICSA.2014.45}}</ref> hence reducing the need for a big upfront design,{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} allows for releasing the software early{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} and continuously.\n\n===DevOps automation===\nDevOps automation can be achieved by repackaging platforms, systems, and applications into reusable building blocks through the use of technologies such as [[Virtual machine|virtual machines]] and [[Docker (software)|containerization]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.devopsdigest.com/full-potential-of-containerization-for-devops-1|title=Unleashing the Full Potential of Containerization for DevOps|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|access-date=20 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/containers-vs-virtual-machines-a-simplified-answer-to-a-complex-question/|title=Containers vs. virtual machines: A simplified answer to a complex question}}</ref>\n\nImplementation of DevOps automation in the IT-organization is heavily dependent on tools, <ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techbeacon.com/devops-automation-best-practices-how-much-too-much|title=DevOps best practices: How much automation do you need?|work=TechBeacon|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref> {{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}which are {{cn span|required|date=March 2019}} to cover different areas of the [[Systems development life cycle|systems development lifecycle]] (SDLC):\n\n# [[Infrastructure as code]] \n# [[CI/CD]]\n# [[Test automation]] \n# [[Container (virtualization)|Containerization]]\n# [[Orchestration (computing)|Orchestration]]\n# [[Software deployment]]\n# [[Software measurement]]\n\n== Adoption ==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nSome articles in the DevOps literature assume or recommend significant participation in DevOps initiatives from outside an organization's [[information technology|IT]] department, e.g.: \"DevOps is just the [[agile software development|agile]] principle, taken to the full enterprise.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://devops.com/2015/03/04/devops-is-agile-for-the-rest-of-the-company/ | title = DevOps is Agile for the Rest of the Company | publisher = DevOps.com| date = 2015-03-04 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn a survey published in January 2016 by the SaaS cloud-computing company [[RightScale]], DevOps adoption increased from 66 percent in 2015 to 74 percent in 2016.{{cn|date=March 2019}} And among larger enterprise organizations, DevOps adoption is even higher \u2013 81 percent.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harvey |first=Cynthia | date= 9 January 2017 | title= 10 Ways DevOps is Changing the Enterprise | url= http://www.datamation.com/data-center/slideshows/10-ways-devops-is-changing-enterprise-it.html | journal=Datamation }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nAdoption of DevOps is being driven by many factors \u2013 including:{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n# Use of agile and other [[software development process|development processes]] and methods;\n# Demand for an increased rate of production releases \u2013 from application and business unit [[Stakeholder (corporate)|stakeholder]]s;\n# Wide availability of virtualized<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.it20.info/misc/virtualizationscomparison.htm\n | title = Virtual Infrastructure products: features comparison | work = Welcome to IT 2.0: Next Generation IT infrastructures}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[Cloud computing|cloud infrastructure]] \u2013 from internal and external providers;\n# Increased usage of [[data center]] automation<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.information-management.com/infodirect/20071026/10000120-1.html | title = Bringing Order to Chaos through Data Center Automation | first = Jennifer | last = Ellard | work = Information Management | publisher = SourceMedia | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611073000/http://www.information-management.com/infodirect/20071026/10000120-1.html | archivedate = 11 June 2010 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[configuration management]] tools;\n# Increased focus on [[test automation]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://devops.com/2015/08/21/impacts-devops-testing/ | title = Impact of DevOps on Testing | publisher = DevOps.com| date = 2015-08-21 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[continuous integration]] methods;\n# A critical mass of publicly available best practices.\n\n== See also==\n* [[Twelve-factor app]]\n*[[Infrastructure as Code]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=Effective DevOps : building a culture of collaboration, affinity, and tooling at scale|last1=Davis|first1=Jennifer|last2=Daniels|first2=Ryn|publisher=O'Reilly|isbn=9781491926437|location=Sebastopol, CA|oclc=951434424|date=2016-05-30}}\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=The DevOps handbook : how to create world-class agility, reliability, and security in technology organizations|last=Kim|first=Gene|last2=Debois|first2=Patrick|last3=Willis|first3=John|last4=Humble|first4=Jez|last5=Allspaw|first5=John|isbn=9781942788003|edition=First|location=Portland, OR|oclc=907166314|date=2015-10-07}}\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=Accelerate: The Science of Lean Software and DevOps: Building and Scaling High Performing Technology Organizations|last=Forsgren|first=Nicole|last2=Humble|first2=Jez|last3=Kim|first3=Gene|isbn=9781942788331|edition=First|publisher=IT Revolution Press|date=March 27, 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Devops}}\n[[Category:Agile software development]]\n[[Category:Software development process]]\n[[Category:Information technology management]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Set of software development practices}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=December 2018}}\n{{Software development process}}\n'''DevOps''' is a set of practices that combines [[software development]] (''Dev'') and [[information technology operations|information-technology operations]] (''Ops'') which aims to shorten the [[systems development life cycle]] and provide [[continuous delivery]] with high [[software quality]].<ref name=\"Mala 2019 p. 16\">{{cite book | last=Mala | first=D.J. | title=Integrating the Internet of Things Into Software Engineering Practices | publisher=IGI Global | series=Advances in Systems Analysis, Software Engineering, and High Performance Computing | year=2019 | isbn=978-1-5225-7791-1 | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GPGCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 | access-date=4 April 2019 | page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"loukides-2012\">{{Cite web|url=http://radar.oreilly.com/2012/06/what-is-devops.html|title=What is DevOps?|last=Loukides|first=Mike|date=7 June 2012|publisher=[[O'Reilly_Media]]}}</ref> \n\n==Definition==\nAcademics and practitioners have not developed a unique definition for the term \"DevOps.\"{{efn|Dyck et. al (2015) \"To our knowledge, there is no uniform definition for the terms release engineering and DevOps. As a consequence, many people use their own definitions or rely on others, which results in confusion about those terms.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1= Andrej |last1= Dyck |first2= Ralf |last2= Penners |first3= Horst |last3= Lichter |title= Towards Definitions for Release Engineering and DevOps |journal=Proceedings of the 2015 IEEE/ACM 3rd International Workshop on Release Engineering |date=2015-05-19 |publisher=[[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] }}</ref>}}{{efn|Jabbari et. al (2016) \"The research results of this study showed the need for a definition as individual studies do not consistently define DevOps.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Ramtin |last1=Jabbari |first2=Nauman |last2=bin Ali |first3=Kai |last3=Petersen |first4=Binish |last4=Tanveer |journal=Proceedings of the 2016 Scientific Workshop |date=May 2016 |publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery]] |title=What is DevOps?: A Systematic Mapping Study on Definitions and Practices }}</ref>}}{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We noticed that there are various gaps in the study of DevOps: There is no consensus of what concepts DevOps covers, nor how DevOps is defined.\"<ref name=\"erich-2017\">{{cite journal |title=A Qualitative Study of DevOps Usage in Practice |first1=F.M.A. |last1=Erich |first2=C. |last2=Amrit |first3=M. |last3=Daneva |journal=Journal of Software: Evolution and Process |volume=29 |issue=6 |date=June 2017 }}</ref>}}{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We discovered that there exists little agreement about the characteristics of DevOps in the academic literature.\"<ref name=\"erich-2017\"/>}}\n\nFrom an academic perspective, [[Len Bass]], [[Ingo Weber]], and [[Liming Zhu]] \u2014 three computer science researchers from the [[CSIRO]] and the [[Software Engineering Institute]] \u2014 suggested defining DevOps as \"a set of practices intended to reduce the time between committing a change to a system and the change being placed into normal production, while ensuring high quality\".<ref>{{cite book|title=DevOps: A Software Architect's Perspective|author1=Bass, Len|author2=Weber, Ingo|author3=Zhu, Liming|isbn=978-0134049847|year=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe term DevOps, however, has been used in multiple contexts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://devops.com/surprise-broad-agreement-on-the-definition-of-devops/|title=Surprise! Broad Agreement on the Definition of DevOps|date=2015-05-13|website=DevOps.com|}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=February 2019}}\n\n==History==\n{{undue|section|date=December 2018}}\nIn 2009, the first conference named devopsdays was held in [[Ghent]], [[Belgium]]. The conference was founded by Belgian consultant, project manager and agile practitioner Patrick Debois.<ref name=\"devops-name\">{{cite web|last=Mezak|first=Steve|title=The Origins of DevOps: What's in a Name?|url=https://devops.com/the-origins-of-devops-whats-in-a-name/|publisher = devops.com|accessdate=6 May 2019|date=25 January 2018}}</ref>{{who|date=December 2018}}<ref name=\"jediblog\">{{cite web|last=Debois|first=Patrick|title=Agile 2008 Toronto|url=http://www.jedi.be/blog/2008/10/09/agile-2008-toronto-agile-infrastructure-and-operations-presentation/|publisher=Just Enough Documented Information|accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> The conference has now spread to other countries.<ref name=\"devopsdays\">{{cite web|last=Debois|first=Patrick|title=DevOps Days|url=http://www.devopsdays.org/|publisher = DevOps Days|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the State of DevOps report was conceived and launched by Alanna Brown at Puppet.<ref name=\"2016 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2016.pdf|title=2016 State of DevOps Report|author1=Alana Brown|author2=Nicole Forsgren|date=2016|publisher=Puppet Labs, DORA (DevOps Research|access-date=2019-05-06|author3=Jez Humble|author4=Nigel Kersten|author5=Gene Kim}}</ref><ref name=\"Alanna Brown\">{{cite web|title=Puppet - Alanna Brown|url=https://puppet.com/blog/author/alanna-brown|publisher=Puppet Labs|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> \nAs of 2014, the annual State of DevOps report was published by Nicole Forsgren, Gene Kim, Jez Humble and others.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|author1=Nicole Forsgren|author2=Gene Kim|author3=Nigel Kersten |author4=Jez Humble|title=2014 State of DevOps Report|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2014.pdf|date=2014|publisher=Puppet Labs, IT Revolution Press and ThoughtWorks |access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\">{{cite web|title=2015 State of DevOps Report|url=https://devops-research.com/assets/state-of-devops-2015.pdf|date=2015|publisher=Puppet Labs, Pwc, IT Revolution Press|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\nIn 2014, they found that DevOps adoption was accelerating.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\nAlso in 2014, Lisa Crispin and Janet Gregory wrote the book More Agile Testing, containing a chapter on testing and DevOps.<ref name=\"More Agile Testing - TOC\">{{cite web|title=More Agile Testing|url=https://agiletester.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/26/2014/09/TOC.pdf|date=October 2014|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref><ref name=\"More Agile Testing\">{{cite book|title=More Agile Testing|url=https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/more-agile-testing/9780133749571/|last=Crispin|first=Lisa|last2=Gregory|first2=Janet|date=October 2014|isbn=9780133749571 |access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Toolchains==\n{{unreliable sources|section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Main|DevOps toolchain}}\nAs DevOps is intended to be a cross-functional mode of working, those that practice the methodology use different sets of tools&mdash;referred to as \"[[DevOps toolchain|toolchains]]\"&mdash;rather than a single one.<ref>{{cite report |title=Gartner Market Trends: DevOps \u2013 Not a Market, but Tool-Centric Philosophy That supports a Continuous Delivery Value Chain |publisher=Gartner |date=18 February 2015}}</ref> These toolchains are expected to fit into one or more of the following categories, reflective of key aspects of the development and delivery process:<ref>{{cite web| title=Integrating DevOps tools into a Service Delivery Platform|last=Edwards|first=Damon|url=http://dev2ops.org/2012/07/integrating-devops-tools-into-a-service-delivery-platform-video/|website=dev2ops.org}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Exploring the ENTIRE DevOps Toolchain for (Cloud) Teams|last=Seroter|first=Richard|url= http://www.infoq.com/articles/devops-toolchain|website=infoq.com}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}\n#Coding \u2013 code development and review, [[Version control|source code management]] tools, code merging \n#Building \u2013 [[continuous integration]] tools, build status\n#Testing \u2013 [[continuous testing]] tools that provide quick and timely feedback on business risks\n#Packaging \u2013 [[Binary repository manager|artifact repository]], application pre-deployment staging\n#Releasing \u2013 change management, release approvals, [[application release automation|release automation]] \n#Configuring \u2013 infrastructure configuration and management, [[infrastructure as code]] tools\n#Monitoring \u2013 [[Application performance management|applications performance monitoring]], end-user experience\n\nSome categories are more essential in a DevOps toolchain than others; especially continuous integration (e.g. [[Jenkins (software)|Jenkins]], [[Gitlab]], [[Bitbucket]] pipelines) and infrastructure as code (e.g., [[Terraform (software)|Terraform]], [[Ansible (software)|Ansible]], [[Puppet (software)|Puppet]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://devops.com/2016/02/05/devops-stack-shoestring-budget/|title=DevOps Stack on a Shoestring Budget|last=Theakanath|first=Thomas|website=devops.com|date=2016-02-05}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}<ref>{{Cite web|title = Stronger DevOps Culture with Puppet and Vagrant|url = https://puppetlabs.com/blog/stronger-devops-culture-with-puppet-and-vagrant|website = Puppet Labs|accessdate = 22 October 2015}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=December 2018}}\n\nForsgren ''et al.'' found that IT performance is strongly correlated with DevOps practices like [[Version control|source code management]] and [[continuous delivery]].<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\n==Relationship to other approaches==\n=== Agile ===\n{{Main|Agile software development}}\nAgile and DevOps serve complementary roles: several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, [[continuous integration]], and [[continuous delivery]] originated in the Agile world, which dates (informally) to the 1990s, and formally to 2001.<ref name=WattsKidd>{{cite web |url=https://www.bmc.com/blogs/devops-vs-agile-whats-the-difference-and-how-are-they-related/ |title=DevOps vs Agile: What's the Difference and How Are They Related? |first1=Stephen |last1=Watts |first2=Chrissy |last2=Kidd |website=bmc.com |date=August 10, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Agile can be viewed as addressing communication gaps between customers and developers, while DevOps addresses gaps between developers and IT operations / infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guru99.com/agile-vs-devops.html |title=Agile Vs. DevOps: What's the difference? |website=guru99.com |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Also, DevOps has focus on the deployment of developed software, whether it is developed via Agile or other methodologies.<ref name=WattsKidd/>.\n\n===ArchOps===\nArchOps presents an extension for DevOps practice, starting from [[software architecture]] artifacts, instead of source code, for operation deployment.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Castellanos |first1=Camilo |last2=Correal |first2=Dario |date=15 September 2018|title=Executing Architectural Models for Big Data Analytics |journal=Lecture Notes in Computer Science |volume=11048 |issue= |pages=364\u2013371 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-00761-4_24 |isbn=978-3-030-00760-7 }}</ref>. ArchOps states that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.\n\n===TestOps===\nTestOps is to hardware development what DevOps is to software development. The idea is a toolchain that links design and ''test'' ''op''eration''s'' together. In the case of hardware, design means [[Electronic design automation|EDA]] tools and the [[CAD]] department, and test means electronic measurement equipment like oscilloscopes and so on.<ref name=\"pathwave\">{{Cite web\n| title = The TestOps Manifesto: A Blueprint for Connected, Agile Design and Test\n| author = Keysight\n| date = 2019-03-19\n| access-date = 2019-09-11\n| url = http://literature.cdn.keysight.com/litweb/pdf/5992-3771EN.pdf\n| language =  \n| quote = Companies that embrace DevOps workflows report 29% greater productivity from their engineers. TestOps \u2013 DevOps for design and test \u2013 promises similar benefits. \n}}</ref>\n\n=== Continuous delivery ===\n{{Main|Continuous delivery}}\nContinuous delivery and DevOps have common goals and are often used in conjunction, but there are subtle differences.<ref name=\"CD_HJ\">{{cite book|title=Continuous Delivery: reliable software releases through build, test, and deployment automation|last=Humble|first=Jez|last2=Farley|first2=David|date=2011|publisher=Pearson Education Inc.|isbn=978-0-321-60191-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hammond|first=Jeffrey|date=9 September 2011|title=The Relationship between DevOps and Continuous Delivery|url=http://blogs.forrester.com/jeffrey_hammond/11-09-09-the_relationship_between_dev_ops_and_continuous_delivery_a_conversation_with_jez_humble_of_thought|journal=Forrester Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> \n\nWhile continuous delivery is focused on automating the processes in [[software delivery]], DevOps also focuses on the organizational change to support great collaboration between the many functions involved.<ref name=\"CD_HJ\" />\n\nDevOps and continuous delivery share a common background in [[Agile software development|agile methods]] and [[lean thinking]]: small and frequent changes with focused value to the end customer.<ref name=\"Agile Now\">{{cite journal|last=Ambler|first=Scott W.|date=12 February 2014|title=We need more Agile IT Now!|url=http://www.drdobbs.com/architecture-and-design/we-need-more-agile-it-now/240169361?queryText=Release%2Bmanagement|journal=Dr. Dobb's the World of Software Development}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} \n[[Lean manufacturing|Lean management]] and continuous delivery are fundamental to delivering value faster, in a sustainable way.<ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\nContinuous delivery focuses on making sure the software is always in a releasable state throughout its lifecycle.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/> This makes it cheaper and less risky to deliver the software.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\nImproved collaboration and communication both between and within organizational teams can help achieve faster [[time to market]], with reduced risks.<ref name=\"CD_LC\">{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1109/MS.2015.27|title = Continuous Delivery: Huge Benefits, but Challenges Too|journal = IEEE Software|volume = 32|issue = 2|pages = 50\u201354|year = 2015|last1 = Chen|first1 = Lianping}}</ref><ref name=\"Micro_Chen\">{{cite conference \n|url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323944215\n|title= Microservices: Architecting for Continuous Delivery and DevOps\n|first= Lianping |last= Chen \n|date= 2018 \n|conference= The IEEE International Conference on Software Architecture (ICSA 2018)\n|conferenceurl= http://icsa-conferences.org/2018/ \n|publisher= IEEE\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===DataOps===\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\n{{Main|DataOps}}\nThe application of continuous delivery and DevOps to data analytics has been termed DataOps. DataOps seeks to integrate data engineering, data integration, data quality, data security, and data privacy with operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tamr.com/from-devops-to-dataops-by-andy-palmer/|title=From DevOps to DataOps, By Andy Palmer - Tamr Inc.|date=7 May 2015|work=Tamr Inc.|access-date=23 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} It applies principles from DevOps, [[Agile software development|Agile Development]] and the [[statistical process control]], used in [[lean manufacturing]], to improve the cycle time of extracting value from data analytics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/data-ops/how-to-become-a-rising-star-with-data-analytics-6e4f611e85dd|title=How to Become a Rising Star with Data Analytics|last=DataKitchen|date=15 March 2017|website=data-ops|access-date=23 August 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Site-reliability engineering ===\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\n{{Main|Site reliability engineering}}\nIn 2003, [[Google]] developed [[site reliability engineering]] (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale high-availability systems while maintaining high-quality end-user experience.<ref>{{cite book|title=Site Reliability Engineering|date=April 2016|publisher=O'Reilly Media|first1=Betsy|last1=Beyer|first2=Chris|last2=Jones|first3=Jennifer|last3=Petoff|first4=Niall Richard|last4=Murphy|isbn=978-1-4919-2909-4}}</ref> While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://devops.com/sre-vs-devops-false-distinction/|title=SRE vs. DevOps \u2014 a False Distinction? - DevOps.com|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Systems administration===\n{{expand section|date=June 2018}}\nDevOps is often viewed as an approach to applying [[systems administrator|systems administration]] work to cloud technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techbeacon.com/sysadmins-survival-guide-devops|title=How to stay relevant in the DevOps era: A SysAdmin's survival guide}}</ref>\n\n===WinOps===\n{{main|WinOps}}\n[[WinOps]] is the term used for DevOps practices for a Microsoft-centric view.{{Citation needed|reason=WinOps is the proper noun of a conference.|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Toyota production system, lean thinking, kaizen===\n{{main|Toyota Production System}}\nToyota production system, TPS, implemented [[continuous improvement process|continuous improvement]], [[kaizen]], and [[lean thinking]] early. The [[Andon (manufacturing)|Andon cord principle]] to create fast feedback, swarm and solve problems stems from TPS. <ref>[https://opensource.com/article/18/11/analyzing-devops Analyzing the DNA of DevOps], Brent Aaron Reed, Willy Schaub, 2018-11-14.</ref><ref>The DevOps Handbook: How to Create World-Class Agility, Reliability, and Security in Technology Organizations, Gene Kim, Patrick Debois, John Willis, Jezz Humble, 2016</ref>\n\n===DevSecOps, Shifting Security Left===\n\nDevSecOps is an augmentation of DevOps to allow for security practices to be integrated into the DevOps approach. The traditional centralised security team model must adopt a federated model allowing each delivery team the ability to factor in the correct security controls into their DevOps practices.\n\n==Goals==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nIT performance can be measured in terms of throughput and stability. <ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\" />\nThroughput can be measured by deployment frequency and lead time for changes; stability can be measured by mean time to recover. The State of DevOps Reports found that investing in practices that increase these throughput and stability measures increase IT performance.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/><ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\nThe goals of DevOps span the entire delivery pipeline. They include:{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n* Improved deployment frequency;  \n* Faster [[time to market]]; \n* Lower failure rate of new releases; \n* Shortened lead time between fixes;\n* Faster mean time to recovery (in the event of a new release crashing or otherwise disabling the current system). \nSimple processes become increasingly programmable and dynamic, using a DevOps approach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newrelic.com/devops/what-is-devops |title=What is DevOps? |publisher=NewRelic.com |accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} DevOps aims to maximize the predictability, efficiency, security, and maintainability of operational processes.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Very often, automation supports this objective.\n\nDevOps integration targets [[Software delivery|product delivery]], [[continuous testing]], [[Software testing#Software quality assurance .28SQA.29|quality testing]], feature development, and [[maintenance release]]s in order to improve reliability and security and provide faster [[Development cycle|development]] and [[Software deployment|deployment]] cycles.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Many of the ideas (and people) involved in DevOps came from the [[enterprise systems management]] and [[agile software development]] movements.<ref name=\"AgileInf2010\">{{cite web|last=Nasrat|first=Paul|title=Agile Infrastructure|url=http://www.infoq.com/presentations/agile-infrastructure|publisher=InfoQ|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nPractices that correlate with deployment frequency are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Continuous delivery\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n\nPractices that correlate with a lead time for change are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n* Automated testing\n\nPractices that correlate with a mean time to recovery for change are:<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n* Using version control for all production artifacts\n* Monitoring system and application health \n\nCompanies {{failed verification span|that practice DevOps|date=February 2019}} have reported significant benefits, including: significantly shorter [[time to market]], improved customer satisfaction, better product quality, more reliable releases, improved productivity and efficiency, and the increased ability to build the right product by fast experimentation.<ref name=\"CD_LC\"/>\n\nThe 2014 State of DevOps Report found that \"IT performance strongly correlates with well-known DevOps practices such as the use of version\ncontrol and continuous delivery.\"<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\nThere is a lack of evidence in academic literature on the effectiveness of DevOps.{{efn|Erich et. al (2017) \"We noticed that there are various gaps in the study of DevOps: [...] There is a lack of evidence on the effectiveness of DevOps.<ref name=\"erich-2017\" />}}\n\n==Cultural change==\nDevOps initiatives can create cultural changes in companies <ref>{{cite report |title=Emerging Technology Analysis: DevOps a Culture Shift, Not a Technology |publisher=Gartner}}</ref> by transforming the way [[Information technology operations|operations]], [[Software developer|developers]], and [[Software testing|testers]] collaborate during the development and delivery processes.<ref name=\"loukides-2012\" /> Getting these groups to work cohesively is a critical challenge in enterprise DevOps adoption.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gartner IT Glossary {{ndash}} devops|website=Gartner|url=http://www.gartner.com/it-glossary/devops/ | access-date= 30 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Jones et al\">{{Cite book| first1 = Stephen| title = Proceedings of the 2nd International Workshop on Quality-Aware Dev ''Ops'' - QUDOS 2016| pages = 7\u201311|last1 = Jones| first2 = Joost| last2 = Noppen|first3 = Fiona| last3 = Lettice| date = 21 July 2016| doi = 10.1145/2945408.2945410  | isbn = 9781450344111}}</ref> DevOps is as much about culture, as it is about the toolchain.<ref name=\"Building a DevOps culture\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oreilly.com/ideas/building-a-devops-culture|title=Building a DevOps culture|author= Mandi Walls|date=September 25, 2015|publisher=O'Reilly}}</ref> \n\n===DevOps as a job title===\n\nWhile DevOps describes an approach to work rather than a distinct role (like [[system administrator]]), job advertisements are increasingly using terms like \"''DevOps Engineer''\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://devops.com/is-devops-a-title/|title=Is DevOps a Title? - DevOps.com|date=20 March 2014|work=DevOps.com|access-date=22 July 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.monster.com/career-advice/article/devops-jobs|title=DevOps: A Job Title or a School of Thought?|work=Monster Career Advice|access-date=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile DevOps reflects complex topics, the DevOps community uses analogies to communicate important concepts,{{relevant inline|date=March 2019}} much like \"[[The Cathedral and the Bazaar]]\" from the open-source community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://devops.stackexchange.com/questions/1403/what-are-known-useful-and-misleading-memes-in-the-devops-culture|title=What are known useful and misleading memes in the DevOps culture?|website=devops.stackexchange.com|access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n* Cattle not Pets: the paradigm of disposable server infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/03/18/servers_pets_or_cattle_cern/|title=Are Your Servers Pets or Cattle?|last=Sharwood|first=Simon|website=[[The Register]]|access-date=2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* 10 deployments per day: the story of Flickr adopting DevOps.\n\n===Building a DevOps culture===\nOrganizational culture is a strong predictor of IT and organizational performance. Cultural practices such as information flow, collaboration, shared responsibilities, learning from failures and new ideas are central to DevOps.<ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/> Team-building and other [[employee engagement]] activities are often used to create an environment that fosters this communication and cultural change within an organization.<ref>{{cite book|last=Walls |first=Mandi | date= 15 April 2013 | title= Building a DevOps Culture| url= https://books.google.com/?id=XO1So8BTj2wC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | publisher=OReilly Media |isbn=9781449368364 }}</ref> Team\u2013building activities can include [[board game]]s, trust activities, and employee engagement seminars.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Roach |first=Patrick | title= Dice Breakers: Using DevOps principles and nerdery to reimagine Team building | url= http://devops.com/2015/10/08/dice-breakers-using-devops-principles-nerdery-reimagine-team-building/| journal=DevOps.com |date=2015-10-08 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe 2015 State of DevOps Report discovered that the top seven measures with the strongest correlation to organizational culture are:\n1. Organizational investment in DevOps:<ref name=\"2015 State of DevOps Report\"/>\n2. Team leaders' experience and effectiveness.\n3. Continuous delivery.\n4. The ability of different disciplines (development, operations, and infosec) to achieve\nwin-win outcomes.\n5. Organizational performance.\n6. Deployment pain.\n7. Lean management practices.\n\n==Deployment==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nCompanies with very frequent releases may require knowledge on DevOps.{{cn|date=March 2019}} For example, the company that operates image hosting website [[Flickr]] developed a DevOps approach to support ten deployments a day.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.slideshare.net/jallspaw/10-deploys-per-day-dev-and-ops-cooperation-at-flickr\n | title = 10+ Deploys Per Day: Dev and Ops Cooperation at Flickr\n| date = 2009-06-23\n}}</ref> Daily deployment cycle would be much higher at organizations producing multi-focus or multi-function applications.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Daily deployment is referred to as [[continuous deployment]]<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.svforum.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Calendar.eventDetail&eventID=13703\n | work = SVForum\n | title = SAM SIG: Applied Lean Startup Ideas: Continuous Deployment at kaChing\n | access-date = 20 June 2011\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121020133600/http://www.svforum.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Calendar.eventDetail&eventID=13703\n | archive-date = 20 October 2012\n | url-status = dead\n }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} or [[continuous delivery]] <ref>{{Cite web\n | url = https://www.cutter.com/article/why-enterprises-must-adopt-devops-enable-continuous-delivery-416516\n | title = Why Enterprises Must Adopt Devops to Enable Continuous Delivery \n | work = [[Cutter IT Journal]] | first = Jez | last = Humble \n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and has been associated with the [[lean startup]] methodology.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url =  http://www.slideshare.net/pascallouis/applied-lean-startup-ideas-continuous-deployment-at-kaching\n | title = Applied Lean Startup Ideas: Continuous Deployment at kaChing\n| date = 2010-05-26\n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} [[Professional association]]s and [[blog|blogs post]]s have formed on the topic since 2009.<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://www.devopsdays.org/events/2009-ghent/\n | title = DevOps Days 2009 Conference\n}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web\n | url = http://dev2ops.org/blog/2010/4/26/devops-meetup-recap.html\n | title = DevOps Meetup Recap | first = Damon | last = Edwards\n}}\n</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Architecturally significant requirements===\nTo practice DevOps effectively, software applications have to meet a set of [[architecturally significant requirements]] (ASRs), such as: deployability, modifiability, testability, and monitorability.<ref name=\"ArchCD_LC\">{{cite conference |title=Towards Architecting for Continuous Delivery|first=Lianping |last=Chen|year=2015|place=Montr\u00e9al, Canada |conference=The 12th Working IEEE/IFIP Conference on Software Architecture(WICSA 2015)|conferenceurl=http://wicsa2015.org/ |publisher=IEEE|doi=10.1109/WICSA.2015.23}}</ref> These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.\n\n===Microservices===\nAlthough in principle it is possible to practice DevOps with any architectural style, the [[microservices]] architectural style is becoming the standard for building continuously deployed systems.<ref name=\"Micro_Chen\"/> Small size service allows the architecture of an individual service to emerge through continuous refactoring,<ref name=\"Ach_Chen\">{{cite conference |title=Towards an Evidence-Based Understanding of Emergence of Architecture through Continuous Refactoring in Agile Software Development|first=Lianping |last=Chen |first2=Muhammad|last2=Ali Babar|date=2014 |conference=The 11th Working IEEE/IFIP Conference on Software Architecture(WICSA 2014)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730053454/http://wicsa2014.org/ |publisher=IEEE|doi=10.1109/WICSA.2014.45}}</ref> hence reducing the need for a big upfront design,{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} allows for releasing the software early{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} and continuously.\n\n===DevOps automation===\nDevOps automation can be achieved by repackaging platforms, systems, and applications into reusable building blocks through the use of technologies such as [[Virtual machine|virtual machines]] and [[Docker (software)|containerization]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.devopsdigest.com/full-potential-of-containerization-for-devops-1|title=Unleashing the Full Potential of Containerization for DevOps|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|access-date=20 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/containers-vs-virtual-machines-a-simplified-answer-to-a-complex-question/|title=Containers vs. virtual machines: A simplified answer to a complex question}}</ref>\n\nImplementation of DevOps automation in the IT-organization is heavily dependent on tools, <ref name=\"2014 State of DevOps Report\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techbeacon.com/devops-automation-best-practices-how-much-too-much|title=DevOps best practices: How much automation do you need?|work=TechBeacon|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref> {{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}which are {{cn span|required|date=March 2019}} to cover different areas of the [[Systems development life cycle|systems development lifecycle]] (SDLC):\n\n# [[Infrastructure as code]] \n# [[CI/CD]]\n# [[Test automation]] \n# [[Container (virtualization)|Containerization]]\n# [[Orchestration (computing)|Orchestration]]\n# [[Software deployment]]\n# [[Software measurement]]\n\n== Adoption ==\n{{unreliable|section|date=March 2019}}\nSome articles in the DevOps literature assume or recommend significant participation in DevOps initiatives from outside an organization's [[information technology|IT]] department, e.g.: \"DevOps is just the [[agile software development|agile]] principle, taken to the full enterprise.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://devops.com/2015/03/04/devops-is-agile-for-the-rest-of-the-company/ | title = DevOps is Agile for the Rest of the Company | publisher = DevOps.com| date = 2015-03-04 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn a survey published in January 2016 by the SaaS cloud-computing company [[RightScale]], DevOps adoption increased from 66 percent in 2015 to 74 percent in 2016.{{cn|date=March 2019}} And among larger enterprise organizations, DevOps adoption is even higher \u2013 81 percent.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harvey |first=Cynthia | date= 9 January 2017 | title= 10 Ways DevOps is Changing the Enterprise | url= http://www.datamation.com/data-center/slideshows/10-ways-devops-is-changing-enterprise-it.html | journal=Datamation }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}}\n\nAdoption of DevOps is being driven by many factors \u2013 including:{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n# Use of agile and other [[software development process|development processes]] and methods;\n# Demand for an increased rate of production releases \u2013 from application and business unit [[Stakeholder (corporate)|stakeholder]]s;\n# Wide availability of virtualized<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.it20.info/misc/virtualizationscomparison.htm\n | title = Virtual Infrastructure products: features comparison | work = Welcome to IT 2.0: Next Generation IT infrastructures}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[Cloud computing|cloud infrastructure]] \u2013 from internal and external providers;\n# Increased usage of [[data center]] automation<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.information-management.com/infodirect/20071026/10000120-1.html | title = Bringing Order to Chaos through Data Center Automation | first = Jennifer | last = Ellard | work = Information Management | publisher = SourceMedia | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611073000/http://www.information-management.com/infodirect/20071026/10000120-1.html | archivedate = 11 June 2010 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[configuration management]] tools;\n# Increased focus on [[test automation]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://devops.com/2015/08/21/impacts-devops-testing/ | title = Impact of DevOps on Testing | publisher = DevOps.com| date = 2015-08-21 }}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|date=March 2019}} and [[continuous integration]] methods;\n# A critical mass of publicly available best practices.\n\n== See also==\n* [[Twelve-factor app]]\n*[[Infrastructure as Code]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=Effective DevOps : building a culture of collaboration, affinity, and tooling at scale|last1=Davis|first1=Jennifer|last2=Daniels|first2=Ryn|publisher=O'Reilly|isbn=9781491926437|location=Sebastopol, CA|oclc=951434424|date=2016-05-30}}\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=The DevOps handbook : how to create world-class agility, reliability, and security in technology organizations|last=Kim|first=Gene|last2=Debois|first2=Patrick|last3=Willis|first3=John|last4=Humble|first4=Jez|last5=Allspaw|first5=John|isbn=9781942788003|edition=First|location=Portland, OR|oclc=907166314|date=2015-10-07}}\n*{{Cite book|url=|title=Accelerate: The Science of Lean Software and DevOps: Building and Scaling High Performing Technology Organizations|last=Forsgren|first=Nicole|last2=Humble|first2=Jez|last3=Kim|first3=Gene|isbn=9781942788331|edition=First|publisher=IT Revolution Press|date=March 27, 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Devops}}\n[[Category:Agile software development]]\n[[Category:Software development process]]\n[[Category:Information technology management]]\n", "name_user": "Sunnyman03", "label": "safe", "comment": "missing citation added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DevOps"}
